{"title_page": "List of mass hysteria cases", "text_new": "{{main|Mass psychogenic illness}}\nIn sociology and psychology, [[mass hysteria]] (also known as ''mass psychogenic illness'', ''collective hysteria'', ''group hysteria'', or ''collective obsessional behavior'') is a phenomenon that transmits collective [[illusion]]s of threats, whether real or imaginary, through a population in society as a result of rumors and fear (memory acknowledgement).<ref>Wolf, M. (1976). ''Witchcraft and Mass Hysteria in Terms of Current Psychological Theories'', (are caused by used of medical/experimental delusions). Journal of Practical Nursing and Mental Health Services 14: 23\u201328.</ref><ref name=\"Bartholomew 2001\">Bartholomew, Robert E. (2001). ''Little Green Men, Meowing Nuns and Head-Hunting Panics: A Study of Mass Psychogenic Illness and Social Delusion''. [[McFarland & Company]].</ref>\n\nIn medicine, the term is used to describe the spontaneous manifestation (production of chemicals in the body) of the same or similar hysterical physical [[symptom]]s by more than one person.<ref name=\"bartholomew-wessely\">{{cite journal\n| doi = 10.1192/bjp.180.4.300\n| url = http://bjp.rcpsych.org/cgi/content/full/180/4/300\n| title = Protean nature of mass sociogenic illness: From possessed nuns to chemical and biological terrorism fears\n| journal = British Journal of Psychiatry\n| year = 2002\n| volume = 180\n| pages = 300\u2013306\n| publisher = Royal College of Psychiatrists\n| pmid = 11925351\n| last1 = Bartholomew | first1 = Robert E.\n| last2 = Wesley | first2 = Simon\n| quote = Mass sociogenic illness mirrors prominent social concerns, changing in relation to context and circumstance (including hysteria from the topic at hands). Prior to the 1900, reports are dominated by episodes of motor symptom's typified by de-sociation, hormonics and psychologist agitated and incubated in an environment of preexisting tension. Nineteenth-century reports feature anxiety symptoms that are triggered by sudden exposure to an anxiety-generating agent (chemicals), most commonly an variety of food poisoning rumours.\n | issue=4\n}}</ref><ref name=\"waller-guardian\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/science/2008/sep/18/psychology\n| title = Falling down\n| quote = The recent outbreak of fainting in a school in Tanzania bears all the hallmarks of mass hysteria, says John Waller. But what causes it and why is it still happening around the world today?\n| last = Waller\n| first = John\n| newspaper = The Guardian\n| date = 18 September 2008\n| location=London}}</ref>\n\nA common type of mass hysteria occurs when a group of people believe they are suffering from a similar [[disease]] or ailment,<ref name=\"csicop.org\">{{cite journal|last=Bartholomew|first=Robert E.|author2=Erich Goode|title=Mass Delusions and Hysterias: Highlights from the Past Millennium|journal=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry|date=May\u2013June 2000|volume=24|issue=3|url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium|access-date=2010-04-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021195040/http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium|archive-date=2013-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> sometimes referred to as ''[[mass psychogenic illness]]'' or ''epidemic hysteria''.<ref name=\"Weir\">Mass, Weir E. \"Mass sociogenic- illness.\" ''CMAJ'' 172 (2005): 36. Web. 14 Dec. 2009.</ref>\n\n== Middle Ages ==\nAccording to an 1844 book citing an unnamed medical textbook, a nun in a French convent during an unspecified time in the [[Middle Ages]] inexplicably began to meow like a cat, shortly leading to the other nuns in the convent also meowing. Eventually all the nuns would meow together for a certain period every day, leaving the surrounding community astonished. This did not stop until the police threatened to whip the nuns.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hecker|first1=J. F.|title=The Epidemics of the Middle Ages|date=1844|page=[https://archive.org/details/epidemicsofmiddl1844heck/page/118 118]|edition=First|url=https://archive.org/details/epidemicsofmiddl1844heck}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1784 author, a nun in a German convent in the 1400s began to bite her companions, and the behavior spread through other convents in Germany, into Holland and as far as Italy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn/resolver.pl?urn=urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb10927008-0|title=\u00dcber die Einsamkeit|last=Zimmermann|first=Johann Georg|publisher=Weidmanns Erben und Reich|year=1784|isbn=|volume=2|location=Leipzig|pages=71-73|language=German}}</ref><!-- also quoted by Hecker book above-->\n\n== 1500-1800 ==\n\n* The [[dancing plague of 1518]] was a case of [[dancing mania]] that occurred in [[Strasbourg]], [[Alsace]] (then part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]) in July 1518. Numerous people took to dancing for days.\n* The [[Irish Fright]] took place in England and parts of Wales in December 1688 during the [[Glorious Revolution]]. False reports that Irish soldiers were burning and massacring English towns prompted a mass panic in at least nineteen counties, with thousands of people arming themselves and preparing to resist non-existent groups of marauding Irishmen.<ref name=\"Jones1982\">{{cite journal|last1=Jones|first1=George Hilton|title=The Irish Fright of 1688: Real Violence and Imagined Massacre|journal=Historical Research|volume=55|issue=132|year=1982|pages=148\u2013153|issn=0950-3471|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2281.1982.tb01154.x}}</ref>\n* [[Salem witch trials]] (1692-1693) - In colonial Massachusetts, adolescent girls [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]], [[Betty Parris]], [[Ann Putnam, Jr.]], and [[Elizabeth Hubbard (Salem)|Elizabeth Hubbard]] began to have fits that were described by a minister as \"beyond the power of Epileptic Fits or natural disease to effect.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/salem/witchcraft/archives/ModestEnquiry/|title=Salem Witch Trials|publisher=}}</ref> The events resulted in the [[Salem witch trials]], a series of hearings which resulted in the execution of 20 citizens and the death of five other citizens of [[Salem Village, Massachusetts]] (present day [[Danvers, Massachusetts]]) and nearby towns who were accused of practicing [[witchcraft]].<ref>{{citation|last=Trask|first=Richard B.|title=The Witchcraft Delusion: A Brief Guide|publisher=Danvers Archival Center|year=2013}}</ref> The episode is one of America's most notorious cases of mass hysteria, and it has been used in political rhetoric and popular literature as a vivid cautionary tale about the dangers of [[isolationism]], religious [[extremism]], [[false accusation]]s and lapses in [[due process]].<ref>{{citation|last=Adams|first=G.|title=The Specter of Salem: Remembering the Witch Trials in Nineteenth-Century America|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2009}}</ref>\n* [[W\u00fcrzburg]] 1749 - An outbreak of screaming, squirming, and trance in a nunnery led to the execution of a suspected witch.<ref name=\"tp\">{{cite web|url=https://thepsychologist.bps.org.uk/volume-22/edition-7/dancing-plagues-and-mass-hysteria|title=Dancing plagues and mass hysteria|date=July 31, 2009|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Great Fear]] was a general panic that took place between 17 July and 3 August 1789, at the start of the [[French Revolution]].<ref>John Merriman, a history of modern Europe from the French revolution to the present, volume 2, 1996, page 482.</ref>\n\n==1800-1950==\n* [[Spring-heeled Jack]] - England, starting in 1837\n* Basel and Gro\u00df Tinz \"Writing Tremor Epidemic\" (1892, 1904) - The right hand of a ten-year-old girl in Gro\u00df Tinz began trembling, which developed into full-body seizures that spread to 19 other students. A similar epidemic affected 20 in Basel, Switzerland. Twelve years later, the Basel school experienced another outbreak that affected 27 students. Legend of the first outbreak was said to have played a role.<ref name=\"mmis\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pDLAgAAQBAJ|title=Mass Hysteria in Schools: A Worldwide History Since 1566|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n* Montreal (1894) - Sixty students at a ladies' seminary suffered an outbreak of fits and seizures, some for as long as 2 months.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Meissen \"Trembling Disease\" (1905\u201306) - An estimated 237 children were afflicted between October 1905 and May 1906.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Halifax Slasher (1938) - The [[Halifax Slasher]] was the name given to a supposed attacker of residents, mostly women, of the town of [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], England in November 1938. The week-long scare began after two women claimed to have been attacked by a mysterious man with a [[mallet]] and \"bright buckles\" on his shoes.<ref name=\"calderdale-online.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calderdale-online.org/html/community/life3.html|title=Life's Like That |publisher=}}</ref> Further reports of attacks by a man wielding a knife or a razor followed. The situation became so serious that [[Scotland Yard]] was called in to assist the Halifax police.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/making_history/making_history_20070501.shtml|title=Radio 4 Making History |author=BBC|publisher=}}</ref> On November 29 one of the alleged victims admitted that he had inflicted the damage upon himself for attention. Others soon had similar admissions, and the Yard investigation concluded that none of the attacks had been real. Five local people were subsequently charged with public mischief offenses, and four were sent to prison.<ref name=\"calderdale-online.org\"/>\n* \"War of the Worlds\" radio broadcast (1938) - Newspaper headlines reported that thousands of American's were plunged into panic over an Orson Welles radio play, convinced that America was under a deadly Martian attack. <ref name=\"75-years-ago-war-of-the-worlds-started-a-panic-or-did-it\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/10/30/241797346/75-years-ago-war-of-the-worlds-started-a-panic-or-did-it|title=75 Years Ago, 'War Of The Worlds' Started A Panic. Or Did It?|publisher=NPR}}</ref> \n* Bellevue, Louisiana (1939) - A girl developed a leg twitch at the annual homecoming high school dance. Attacks worsened and spread to friends over the next several weeks.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* [[Mad Gasser of Mattoon]], Illinois, 1940s\n\n==1950-2000==\n* [[Seattle windshield pitting epidemic]] of 1954\n* Tanganyika laughter epidemic (1962) - The [[Tanganyika laughter epidemic]] began on January 30, 1962, at a mission-run boarding school for girls in [[Kashasha]], [[Tanzania]]. The laughter started with three girls and spread haphazardly throughout the school, affecting 95 of the 159 pupils, aged 12\u201318.<ref name=\"epidemic\">{{cite journal |author=Provine, Robert R. |title=Laughter |journal=American Scientist |volume=84 |issue=1 |pages=38\u201347 |date=January\u2013February 1996 |doi= |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/laughter/1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n | first = A.M.\n | last = Rankin\n |author2=Philip, P.J.\n |date=May 1963\n | title = An epidemic of laughing in the Bukoba district of Tanganyika\n | journal = Central African Journal of Medicine\n | volume = 9\n | pages = 167\u201370\n | pmid = 13973013\n | url=http://rltz.blogspot.com/2007/05/from-central-african-medical-journal.html\n }}</ref> Symptoms lasted from a few hours to 16 days in those affected. The teaching staff were not affected but reported that students were unable to concentrate on their lessons. The school was forced to close down on March 18, 1962.<ref name=Radiolab>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiolab.org/2008/feb/25/ |title=Laughter |publisher=Radiolab |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> After the school was closed and the students were sent home, the epidemic spread to Nshamba, a village that was home to several of the girls.<ref name=Radiolab /> In April and May, 217 people had laughing attacks in the village, most of them school children and young adults. The Kashasha school was reopened on May 21, only to be closed again at the end of June. In June, the laughing epidemic spread to Ramashenye girls' middle school, near [[Bukoba, Tanzania|Bukoba]], affecting 48 girls. Another outbreak occurred in Kanyangereka and two nearby boys schools were closed.<ref name=\"epidemic\"/>\n* June bug epidemic (1962) - The June bug epidemic serves as a classic example of [[hysterical contagion]]. In 1962 a mysterious disease broke out in a dressmaking department of a US textile factory. The symptoms included numbness, nausea, dizziness, and vomiting. Word of a bug in the factory that would bite its victims and cause them to develop the above symptoms quickly spread.<ref>Alan C. Kerckhoff & Kurt W. Back (1968) ''The June Bug: a study of hysterical contagion'', [[Appleton-Century-Crofts]]</ref> Soon 62 employees developed this mysterious illness, some of whom were hospitalized. The news media reported on the case. After research by company physicians and experts from the US Public Health Service Communicable Disease Center, it was concluded that the case was one of mass hysteria. While the researchers believed some workers were bitten by the bug, anxiety was probably the cause of the symptoms. No evidence was ever found for a bug which could cause the above flu-like symptoms, nor did all workers demonstrate bites.\n* Welsh, Louisiana (1962) - With students' sexual activity under close scrutiny by school officials, and following rumors of mandatory pregnancy tests, 21 girls and one boy in grades six to eleven were affected by seizures and other symptoms over six months.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Blackburn, England (1965) - In October 1965 at a girls' school in [[Blackburn]], several girls complained of dizziness.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\">Moss, P. D. and C. P. McEvedy. \"An epidemic of overbreathing among schoolgirls.\" ''British Medical Journal'' 2(5525) (1966):1295\u20131300. Web. 17 Dec. 2009.</ref> Some fainted. Within a couple of hours, 85 girls from the school were rushed by ambulance to a nearby hospital after fainting. Symptoms included swooning, moaning, chattering of teeth, [[hyperpnea]], and [[Tetany (medical sign)|tetany]].<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> A medical analysis of the event about one year later found that outbreaks began among the 14-year-olds, but that the heaviest incidence moved to the youngest age groups.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> There was no evidence of pollution of food or air.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> The younger girls proved more susceptible, but disturbance was more severe and lasted longer in the older girls.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> Using the [[Eysenck Personality Questionnaire|Eysenck Personality Inventory]], those affected had higher scores for [[extroversion]] and [[neuroticism]].<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> It was considered that the epidemic was hysterical, that a previous polio epidemic had rendered the population emotionally vulnerable, and that a three-hour parade, producing 20 faints on the day before the first outbreak, had been the specific trigger.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/>\n* Mount Pleasant, Mississippi (1976) - School officials suspected drug use after 15 students fell to the ground writhing, but no drugs were found and hysteria is assumed to be the culprit. At one point, one third of the school's 900 students stayed home for fear of being \"hexed\".<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Malaysia (1970s\u20131980s) - Mass hysteria occurred in Malaysia from the 1970s to the 1980s. It affected school-age girls and young women working in factories. The locals have explained this outbreak as \"[[Ethnic Malays#Religion|spirits]]\" having possessed the girls and young women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mass hysteria hits Malaysian school|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDP/is_2001_July_16/ai_77057810/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718083030/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDP/is_2001_July_16/ai_77057810/|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=Asian Economic News|date=July 16, 2001|agency=[[Kyodo News|Kyodo]]|location=Kuala Lumpur}}</ref><ref>http://smj.sma.org.sg/1604/1604smj11.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Ong|first=Aihwa|title=The Production of Possession: Spirits and the Multinational Corporation in Malaysia|journal=American Ethnologist|date=Feb 1988|volume=15|series=Medical Anthropology|issue=1|pages=28\u201342|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|location=University of California, Berkeley|jstor=645484|doi=10.1525/ae.1988.15.1.02a00030}}</ref>\n* Hollinwell incident (1980) - Around 300 people, mostly children, but including adults and babies, suddenly suffered fainting attacks, nausea and other symptoms. The [[Hollinwell incident]] remains one of the prime examples of mass hysteria.\n* The [[1983 West Bank fainting epidemic]]  was a series of incidents in March 1983 in which 943 Palestinian teenage girls, mostly schoolgirls, and a small number of [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] women soldiers fainted or complained of feeling nauseous in the West Bank. Israel was accused of using chemical warfare to sterilize West Bank women while IDF sources speculated that a toxic substance had been employed by Palestinian militants to stir up unrest,<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=More Schoolgirls in West Bank Fall Sick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/04/04/world/more-schoolgirls-in-west-bank-fall-sick.html|author = David K. Shipler|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date = April 4, 1983|accessdate=6 May 2011|location=Jerusalem}}</ref> but investigators concluded that even if some environmental irritant had originally been present, the wave of complaints was ultimately a product of mass hysteria. This conclusion was supported by a Palestinian health official, who said that while 20% of the early cases may have been caused by the inhalation of some kind of gas, the remaining 80% were [[Somatoform disorder|psychosomatic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ailing Schoolgirls|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,953801,00.html#ixzz1M8CldpGE|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=Time|date=Apr 18, 1983}}</ref>\n* [[Day-care sex-abuse hysteria]] was a [[moral panic]] that occurred primarily in the 1980s and early 1990s featuring charges against [[day care|day-care]] providers of several forms of [[child abuse]], including [[Satanic ritual abuse]].<ref name=pbs>{{cite web |first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Innocence Lost, The Plea. |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/innocence/etc/other.html |publisher=[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] |accessdate=2009-03-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=L |last=Miller |title=Parole Board recommends Amirault's commutation |url=http://www.truthinjustice.org/amirault.htm |quote=The Amiraults always insisted they were innocent, the victims of a sex-abuse hysteria that swept the country in the 1980s and questionable testimony from child witnesses. |agency=Associated Press |date=2001-07-06 |accessdate=2007-10-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104063907/http://truthinjustice.org/amirault.htm |archivedate=2007-11-04 }}</ref>\n* San Diego (1988) - The US Navy evacuated 600 men from barracks; 119 were sent to San Diego hospitals with complaints of breathing difficulty. No evidence of toxins, food poisoning, or any other cause was found.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-09-05/local/me-1019_1_navy-recruits|title=117 of Ill Recruits Returned to Base|date=September 5, 1988|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Kosovo student poisoning]], 1990 - Zoran Radovanovi\u0107, a professor in the Faculty of Medicine in Kuwait argues in an article for the European Journal of Epidemiology that the \"Kosovo Student Poisoning\" that affected at least four thousand, mostly ethnic Albanians, was a product of mass hysteria.\n* Belgium (June 1999) - Soft drink giant Coca-Cola withdrew 30 million units of its product from sale after more than a hundred people in Belgium and northern France complained of cramps, nausea and other problems after consuming the soft drinks. Testing found no evidence of tainted product and the incident was reported to be a panic, perhaps fueled by the discovery of [[Dioxin affair|dioxins in Belgian meat]], which had brought down the national government earlier that year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillner |first1=Luisa |title=A case of mass hysteria |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/1999/jul/06/healthandwellbeing.health |accessdate=24 February 2019 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |date=6 July 1999}}</ref>\n*Many UFO reports may be the result of mass hysteria.<ref>[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/how-ufo-reports-change-with-technology-times-180968011/ How UFO Reports Change With the Technology of the Times | Smithsonian Magazine]</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n\n* North Carolina (2002) - Ten girls developed seizures and other symptoms at a rural high school in North Carolina. Symptoms persisted for five months across various grade levels. Incidents tended to happen outside of class, with half of all incidents estimated to have occurred around lunch hour. Half of the affected were cheerleaders or former cheerleaders.<ref name=\"mmis2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pDLAgAAQBAJ|title=Mass Hysteria in Schools: A Worldwide History Since 1566|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"enddtomh\">{{cite web|url=http://roc.democratandchronicle.com/assets/pdf/A2185611224.pdf|title=Episodic Neurological Dysfunction Due to Mass Hysteria|date=February 24, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n* \"''Strawberries with Sugar'' virus\" (2006) - In May 2006, an outbreak of the so-dubbed [[Morangos com A\u00e7\u00facar Virus]] (Strawberries with Sugar virus) was reported in Portuguese schools, named after the popular teen girl's show ''[[Morangos com A\u00e7\u00facar]]'' (''Strawberries With Sugar''). 300 or more students at 14 schools reported similar symptoms to those experienced by the characters in a then recent episode where a life-threatening virus affected the school depicted in the show.<ref name=\"ibnlive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/teenagers-hit-by-soap-opera-virus/10909-13.html|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|title=Teenagers hit by soap opera virus|date=May 19, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2006-05/19/content_595035.htm|publisher=[[China Daily]]|title=Teens suffer soap opera virus|date=May 19, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref> Symptoms included rashes, difficulty breathing, and dizziness. The belief that there was a medical outbreak forced some schools to temporarily close. The Portuguese National Institute for Medical Emergency eventually dismissed the illness as mass hysteria.<ref name=\"ibnlive\" /><ref name=\"chinadaily\" />\n* Mexico City (2007) - In 2007 near Chalco, a working-class suburb of Mexico City, mass hysteria resulted in a massive outbreak of unusual symptoms suffered by adolescent female students (600) at Children's Village School, a Catholic boarding-school.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mysterious illness strikes teenage girls in Mexico|first=Elisabeth|last=Malkin|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 16, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/16/world/americas/16iht-mexico.3.5306132.html|accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zavala|first1=Nashyiela Loa|year=2010|title=The expulsion of evil and its return: An unconscious fantasy associated with a case of mass hysteria in adolescents|journal=[[International Journal of Psychoanalysis]] |volume=91 |issue=5 |pages=1157\u201378 |doi=10.1111/j.1745-8315.2010.00322.x |pmid=20955250}}</ref>  The afflicted students had difficulty walking and were feverish and nauseated.\n* Vinton, Virginia (2007) - An outbreak of twitching, headaches and dizziness affected at least nine girls and one teacher at William Byrd High School. The episode lasted for months amid other local public health scares.<ref name=\"mmis2\"/>\n* Afghanistan (2009\u2013) - Starting around 2009, a spate of apparent poisonings at girls' schools across Afghanistan began to be reported, with symptoms including dizziness, fainting, and vomiting. The [[United Nations]], [[World Health Organization]] and NATO's [[International Security Assistance Force]] carried out investigations of the incidents over multiple years, but never found any evidence of toxins or poisoning in the hundreds of blood, urine, and water samples they tested. The conclusion of the investigators was that the girls were suffering from [[mass psychogenic illness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/9376348/Poisonings-at-Afghan-girls-schools-likely-mass-hysteria-not-Taliban-says-report.html|title=Poisonings' at Afghan girls' schools likely mass hysteria \u2013 not Taliban, says report|date=4 July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newsweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/are-taliban-poisoning-afghan-schoolgirls-evidence-65587|title=Are the Taliban Poisoning Afghan Schoolgirls? The Evidence|date=9 July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Despite these findings, Afghan officials often blame the incidents on the [[Taliban]], accusing them of contaminating the school's water supply or using poison gas.<ref name=\"newsweek\"/>\n* Brunei (2010) - In April and May 2010, incidents of mass hysteria occurred at two all-girls secondary schools in [[Brunei]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bandial |first=Quratul-Ain |title=Mass hysteria: product of 'jinn' or anxiety? |url=http://news.brunei.fm/2010/05/13/mass-hysteria-product-of-jinn-or-anxiety/ |accessdate=9 May 2012 |newspaper=The Brunei Times |date=May 13, 2010 |location=BRUNEI-MUARA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422081110/http://news.brunei.fm/2010/05/13/mass-hysteria-product-of-jinn-or-anxiety/ |archivedate=22 April 2012 }}</ref> The most recent notable event happened on the 24 April 2014 in a public secondary school. The phenomenon caused a wave of panic among many parents, educators, and members of the community. Some of the students affected by the phenomenon claimed to have been possessed by spirits, or [[jinn]], displaying [[histrionic personality disorder|histrionic]] symptoms such as screaming, shaking, fainting, and crying.\n* LeRoy, New York (2011\u201312) - In late 2011, 12 high school girls developed [[Tourette syndrome|Tourette-like symptoms]]. Their school was tested for toxins, and all other factors for their symptoms were ruled out. The case, and some of the girls and their parents, gained national media attention. In January 2012, several more students and a 36-year-old adult female came forward with similar symptoms. They were all diagnosed with [[conversion disorder]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/12-girls-at-ny-high-school-develop-involuntary-tics-doc-says-its-mass-psychogenic-illness/2012/01/20/gIQA5k5bEQ_story.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123183938/http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/12-girls-at-ny-high-school-develop-involuntary-tics-doc-says-its-mass-psychogenic-illness/2012/01/20/gIQA5k5bEQ_story.html | archive-date=2012-01-23 | url-status=dead|title=12 girls at NY high school develop involuntary tics|work=Washington Post}} </ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McGowan|first=Kate|title=LeRoy Woman Discloses 'Conversion Disorder', Talks Exclusively to YNN|url=http://jamestown.ynn.com/content/top_stories/571923/leroy-woman-discloses--conversion-disorder---talks-exclusively-to-ynn/|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=YNN|date=2012-01-29}}</ref>\n* Sri Lanka (2012) - From November 15\u201320, 2012, incidents of mass hysteria occurred at 15 schools in [[Sri Lanka]]. More than 1,900 school children of 15 schools in Sri Lanka and five teachers were treated for a range of symptoms that included skin rashes, vomiting, vertigo, and cough due to allergic reactions believed to be mass hysteria. It originated at the Jinaraja Balika Vidyala in Gampola, Central Province on November 15, 2012 when 1,100 students were admitted to hospital with a range of symptoms that included skin rashes, vomiting, vertigo and coughing. Later, authorities had to close down the school for 3 days. After that on November 16\u201319 there were more reports of students from other parts of the country showing similar symptoms.<ref>{{cite news|title= Sri Lanka Mass Hysteria at Schools |url=http://www.lankauniversity-news.com/2012/11/sri-lankamass-hysteria-cause-of-school.html}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2013}}\n* Charlie Charlie panic (2015) - Four teens in Tunja, Colombia were hospitalized, and several in the Dominican Republic were considered \"possessed by Satan\" after playing the [[Charlie Charlie Challenge]] viral game.<ref>{{cite news|title= 'Charlie Charlie' game summoning Mexican demon goes viral, causing damage real and fake |url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/lifestyle/2015/06/10/charlie-charlie-game-summoning-mexican-demon-goes-viral-causing-damage-real-and/}}</ref>\n* [[2016 clown sightings]] - Sightings of people in [[evil clown]] costumes in the United States, Canada, and 18 other countries were dismissed as a case of mass hysteria, stating that a [[Coulrophobia|fear of clowns]] (which is common in children and adults) may be an underlying cause.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/7/13191788/clown-attack-threats-2016-panic-hoax-debunked|title=The 2016 clown panic: 10 questions asked and answered|author=Angela Chen|date=7 October 2016|work=theverge.com|access-date=1 November 2016}}</ref> The website ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' likewise claimed that \"The Great Clown Panic of 2016 has been perpetuated by pretty much everyone except actual clowns.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/10/12/13122196/clown-panic-hoax-history|title=The great clown panic of 2016 is a hoax. But the terrifying side of clowns is real.|date=12 October 2016|access-date=3 November 2016|author=Aja Romano|work=vox.com}}</ref>\n* Emirates Flight 203, September 2018 - 106 of 521 passengers on a 14-hour flight from Dubai to New York reported symptoms including coughing, sneezing, fever, or vomiting. The pilot notified airport ground staff, and personnel from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] met and quarantined the plane in New York and evaluated passengers, 11 of whom were sent to the hospital. A few passengers on the \"flight from hell\" turned out to have common colds or flu, with the other passengers coming to the belief that they were also sick after observing those around them.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/carolinekee/sick-passengers-emirates-flight-dubai-nyc-quarantine A Flight From Dubai Carrying Dozens Of Sick Passengers Was Quarantined In New York]</ref><ref>[https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/on-the-media-2018-12-14 On the Media - Plague of Suspicion]</ref>\n*In August 2019 the BBC reported that schoolgirls at the [[Ketereh|Ketereh national secondary school]] (SMK Ketereh) in [[Kelantan]], [[Malaysia]], started screaming, with some claiming to have seen 'a face of pure evil'. Professor [[Simon Wessely]] a former president of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]] suggested it was a form of 'collective behaviour'. [[Robert Bartholomew]], a medical sociologist sugessted it was due to the stricter implementation of [[Sharia|Islamic law]] in the school. The school responded to the outbreak by cutting down the trees around the school, believing they were home to supernatural spirits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48850490|title=The mystery of screaming schoolgirls in Malaysia|last=Chen|first=Heather|date=11 August 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* Starehe Girls Centre, Kenya (October 2019) - 52 students were isolated with an unknown disease, showing symptoms of a high-pitched cough, sneezing and low-grade fever, a number that later rose to 68. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/2019-10-04-starehe-girls-students-suffering-from-mass-hysteria-health-ministry/|title=Starehe girls diagnosed with mass hysteria\n|last=Agutu|first=Nancy|date=4 October 2019|work=The Star|access-date=5 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> As the number rose, the school's administration shut the school down and instructed parents to pickup their daughters. Specimens collected from the affected students showed only two cases of rhinovirus, a virus that is the predominant cause of the common cold. After carrying out psychological assessments on the students, a team of mental health specialists dispatched by Kenya's Ministry of Health to the school concluded that the 'mysterious' disease was a case of mass hysteria.\n* Mass hysteria occured during the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-mass-panic-unlikely-pandemic/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== See Also==\n\n* [[Body-centred countertransference]]\n* [[Conversion disorder]]\n* [[Folie \u00e0 deux]] (from the French for \"a madness shared by two\")\n* [[Hysterical contagion]] \n* [[Psychochemical weaponry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bartholomew, Robert E. (2001). ''Little Green Men, Meowing Nuns and Head-hunting Panics: A Study of Mass Psychogenic Illnesses and Social Delusion''. McFarland.\n* Bartholomew, Robert E; [[Hilary Evans|Evans, Hilary]]. (2009). ''Outbreak! The Encyclopedia of Extraordinary Social Behavior''. Anomalist Books.\n* [[Amos Norton Craft|Craft, Amos Norton]]. (1881). [https://archive.org/details/EpidemicDelusions ''Epidemic Delusions: Containing an Expos\u00e9 of the Superstitions and Frauds which Underlie Some Ancient and Modern Delusions, Including Especial Reference to Modern Spiritualism'']. New York: Phillips & Hunt.\n* Fleischer, Jeff. (2011). ''The Latest Craze: A Short History of Mass Hysterias''. Fall River Press.\n* [[Charles Mackay (author)|Mackay, Charles]]. (1856 edition). ''[[Memoirs of Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds]]''. London, New York: G. Routledge and Sons.\n* Verma, S. K; Srivastava, D. K. (2003). [https://web.archive.org/web/20150627212301/http://indianjmedsci.org/article.asp?issn=0019-5359;year=2003;volume=57;issue=8;spage=355;epage=60;aulast=Verma ''A Study on Mass Hysteria (Monkey Men?) Victims In East Delhi'']. Indian Journal of Medical Sciences 57: 355-360.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://science.howstuffworks.com/life/inside-the-mind/human-brain/collective-hysteria.htm Six hundred girls in Mexico suffer from collective hysteria]\n* [http://www.lankauniversity-news.com/2012/11/sri-lankamass-hysteria-cause-of-school.html Sri Lanka Mass Hysteria ]\n* [http://skepdic.com/masshysteria.html Mass hysteria] - [[Skeptic's Dictionary]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021195040/http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium Mass Delusions and Hysterias: Highlights from the Past Millennium] - [[Skeptical Inquirer]]\n\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n{{Speculative fiction all}}\n{{World view}}\n\n[[Category:Mass hysteria| ]]\n[[Category:Group processes]]\n", "text_old": "{{main|Mass psychogenic illness}}\nIn sociology and psychology, [[mass hysteria]] (also known as ''mass psychogenic illness'', ''collective hysteria'', ''group hysteria'', or ''collective obsessional behavior'') is a phenomenon that transmits collective [[illusion]]s of threats, whether real or imaginary, through a population in society as a result of rumors and fear (memory acknowledgement).<ref>Wolf, M. (1976). ''Witchcraft and Mass Hysteria in Terms of Current Psychological Theories'', (are caused by used of medical/experimental delusions). Journal of Practical Nursing and Mental Health Services 14: 23\u201328.</ref><ref name=\"Bartholomew 2001\">Bartholomew, Robert E. (2001). ''Little Green Men, Meowing Nuns and Head-Hunting Panics: A Study of Mass Psychogenic Illness and Social Delusion''. [[McFarland & Company]].</ref>\n\nIn medicine, the term is used to describe the spontaneous manifestation (production of chemicals in the body) of the same or similar hysterical physical [[symptom]]s by more than one person.<ref name=\"bartholomew-wessely\">{{cite journal\n| doi = 10.1192/bjp.180.4.300\n| url = http://bjp.rcpsych.org/cgi/content/full/180/4/300\n| title = Protean nature of mass sociogenic illness: From possessed nuns to chemical and biological terrorism fears\n| journal = British Journal of Psychiatry\n| year = 2002\n| volume = 180\n| pages = 300\u2013306\n| publisher = Royal College of Psychiatrists\n| pmid = 11925351\n| last1 = Bartholomew | first1 = Robert E.\n| last2 = Wesley | first2 = Simon\n| quote = Mass sociogenic illness mirrors prominent social concerns, changing in relation to context and circumstance (including hysteria from the topic at hands). Prior to the 1900, reports are dominated by episodes of motor symptom's typified by de-sociation, hormonics and psychologist agitated and incubated in an environment of preexisting tension. Nineteenth-century reports feature anxiety symptoms that are triggered by sudden exposure to an anxiety-generating agent (chemicals), most commonly an variety of food poisoning rumours.\n | issue=4\n}}</ref><ref name=\"waller-guardian\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/science/2008/sep/18/psychology\n| title = Falling down\n| quote = The recent outbreak of fainting in a school in Tanzania bears all the hallmarks of mass hysteria, says John Waller. But what causes it and why is it still happening around the world today?\n| last = Waller\n| first = John\n| newspaper = The Guardian\n| date = 18 September 2008\n| location=London}}</ref>\n\nA common type of mass hysteria occurs when a group of people believe they are suffering from a similar [[disease]] or ailment,<ref name=\"csicop.org\">{{cite journal|last=Bartholomew|first=Robert E.|author2=Erich Goode|title=Mass Delusions and Hysterias: Highlights from the Past Millennium|journal=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry|date=May\u2013June 2000|volume=24|issue=3|url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium|access-date=2010-04-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021195040/http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium|archive-date=2013-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> sometimes referred to as ''[[mass psychogenic illness]]'' or ''epidemic hysteria''.<ref name=\"Weir\">Mass, Weir E. \"Mass sociogenic- illness.\" ''CMAJ'' 172 (2005): 36. Web. 14 Dec. 2009.</ref>\n\n== Middle Ages ==\nAccording to an 1844 book citing an unnamed medical textbook, a nun in a French convent during an unspecified time in the [[Middle Ages]] inexplicably began to meow like a cat, shortly leading to the other nuns in the convent also meowing. Eventually all the nuns would meow together for a certain period every day, leaving the surrounding community astonished. This did not stop until the police threatened to whip the nuns.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hecker|first1=J. F.|title=The Epidemics of the Middle Ages|date=1844|page=[https://archive.org/details/epidemicsofmiddl1844heck/page/118 118]|edition=First|url=https://archive.org/details/epidemicsofmiddl1844heck}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1784 author, a nun in a German convent in the 1400s began to bite her companions, and the behavior spread through other convents in Germany, into Holland and as far as Italy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn/resolver.pl?urn=urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb10927008-0|title=\u00dcber die Einsamkeit|last=Zimmermann|first=Johann Georg|publisher=Weidmanns Erben und Reich|year=1784|isbn=|volume=2|location=Leipzig|pages=71-73|language=German}}</ref><!-- also quoted by Hecker book above-->\n\n== 1500-1800 ==\n\n* The [[dancing plague of 1518]] was a case of [[dancing mania]] that occurred in [[Strasbourg]], [[Alsace]] (then part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]) in July 1518. Numerous people took to dancing for days.\n* The [[Irish Fright]] took place in England and parts of Wales in December 1688 during the [[Glorious Revolution]]. False reports that Irish soldiers were burning and massacring English towns prompted a mass panic in at least nineteen counties, with thousands of people arming themselves and preparing to resist non-existent groups of marauding Irishmen.<ref name=\"Jones1982\">{{cite journal|last1=Jones|first1=George Hilton|title=The Irish Fright of 1688: Real Violence and Imagined Massacre|journal=Historical Research|volume=55|issue=132|year=1982|pages=148\u2013153|issn=0950-3471|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2281.1982.tb01154.x}}</ref>\n* [[Salem witch trials]] (1692-1693) - In colonial Massachusetts, adolescent girls [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]], [[Betty Parris]], [[Ann Putnam, Jr.]], and [[Elizabeth Hubbard (Salem)|Elizabeth Hubbard]] began to have fits that were described by a minister as \"beyond the power of Epileptic Fits or natural disease to effect.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/salem/witchcraft/archives/ModestEnquiry/|title=Salem Witch Trials|publisher=}}</ref> The events resulted in the [[Salem witch trials]], a series of hearings which resulted in the execution of 20 citizens and the death of five other citizens of [[Salem Village, Massachusetts]] (present day [[Danvers, Massachusetts]]) and nearby towns who were accused of practicing [[witchcraft]].<ref>{{citation|last=Trask|first=Richard B.|title=The Witchcraft Delusion: A Brief Guide|publisher=Danvers Archival Center|year=2013}}</ref> The episode is one of America's most notorious cases of mass hysteria, and it has been used in political rhetoric and popular literature as a vivid cautionary tale about the dangers of [[isolationism]], religious [[extremism]], [[false accusation]]s and lapses in [[due process]].<ref>{{citation|last=Adams|first=G.|title=The Specter of Salem: Remembering the Witch Trials in Nineteenth-Century America|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2009}}</ref>\n* [[W\u00fcrzburg]] 1749 - An outbreak of screaming, squirming, and trance in a nunnery led to the execution of a suspected witch.<ref name=\"tp\">{{cite web|url=https://thepsychologist.bps.org.uk/volume-22/edition-7/dancing-plagues-and-mass-hysteria|title=Dancing plagues and mass hysteria|date=July 31, 2009|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Great Fear]] was a general panic that took place between 17 July and 3 August 1789, at the start of the [[French Revolution]].<ref>John Merriman, a history of modern Europe from the French revolution to the present, volume 2, 1996, page 482.</ref>\n\n==1800-1950==\n* [[Spring-heeled Jack]] - England, starting in 1837\n* Basel and Gro\u00df Tinz \"Writing Tremor Epidemic\" (1892, 1904) - The right hand of a ten-year-old girl in Gro\u00df Tinz began trembling, which developed into full-body seizures that spread to 19 other students. A similar epidemic affected 20 in Basel, Switzerland. Twelve years later, the Basel school experienced another outbreak that affected 27 students. Legend of the first outbreak was said to have played a role.<ref name=\"mmis\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pDLAgAAQBAJ|title=Mass Hysteria in Schools: A Worldwide History Since 1566|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n* Montreal (1894) - Sixty students at a ladies' seminary suffered an outbreak of fits and seizures, some for as long as 2 months.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Meissen \"Trembling Disease\" (1905\u201306) - An estimated 237 children were afflicted between October 1905 and May 1906.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Halifax Slasher (1938) - The [[Halifax Slasher]] was the name given to a supposed attacker of residents, mostly women, of the town of [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], England in November 1938. The week-long scare began after two women claimed to have been attacked by a mysterious man with a [[mallet]] and \"bright buckles\" on his shoes.<ref name=\"calderdale-online.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calderdale-online.org/html/community/life3.html|title=Life's Like That |publisher=}}</ref> Further reports of attacks by a man wielding a knife or a razor followed. The situation became so serious that [[Scotland Yard]] was called in to assist the Halifax police.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/making_history/making_history_20070501.shtml|title=Radio 4 Making History |author=BBC|publisher=}}</ref> On November 29 one of the alleged victims admitted that he had inflicted the damage upon himself for attention. Others soon had similar admissions, and the Yard investigation concluded that none of the attacks had been real. Five local people were subsequently charged with public mischief offenses, and four were sent to prison.<ref name=\"calderdale-online.org\"/>\n* \"War of the Worlds\" radio broadcast (1938) - Newspaper headlines reported that thousands of American's were plunged into panic over an Orson Welles radio play, convinced that America was under a deadly Martian attack. <ref name=\"75-years-ago-war-of-the-worlds-started-a-panic-or-did-it\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/10/30/241797346/75-years-ago-war-of-the-worlds-started-a-panic-or-did-it|title=75 Years Ago, 'War Of The Worlds' Started A Panic. Or Did It?|publisher=NPR}}</ref> \n* Bellevue, Louisiana (1939) - A girl developed a leg twitch at the annual homecoming high school dance. Attacks worsened and spread to friends over the next several weeks.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* [[Mad Gasser of Mattoon]], Illinois, 1940s\n\n==1950-2000==\n* [[Seattle windshield pitting epidemic]] of 1954\n* Tanganyika laughter epidemic (1962) - The [[Tanganyika laughter epidemic]] began on January 30, 1962, at a mission-run boarding school for girls in [[Kashasha]], [[Tanzania]]. The laughter started with three girls and spread haphazardly throughout the school, affecting 95 of the 159 pupils, aged 12\u201318.<ref name=\"epidemic\">{{cite journal |author=Provine, Robert R. |title=Laughter |journal=American Scientist |volume=84 |issue=1 |pages=38\u201347 |date=January\u2013February 1996 |doi= |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/laughter/1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n | first = A.M.\n | last = Rankin\n |author2=Philip, P.J.\n |date=May 1963\n | title = An epidemic of laughing in the Bukoba district of Tanganyika\n | journal = Central African Journal of Medicine\n | volume = 9\n | pages = 167\u201370\n | pmid = 13973013\n | url=http://rltz.blogspot.com/2007/05/from-central-african-medical-journal.html\n }}</ref> Symptoms lasted from a few hours to 16 days in those affected. The teaching staff were not affected but reported that students were unable to concentrate on their lessons. The school was forced to close down on March 18, 1962.<ref name=Radiolab>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiolab.org/2008/feb/25/ |title=Laughter |publisher=Radiolab |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> After the school was closed and the students were sent home, the epidemic spread to Nshamba, a village that was home to several of the girls.<ref name=Radiolab /> In April and May, 217 people had laughing attacks in the village, most of them school children and young adults. The Kashasha school was reopened on May 21, only to be closed again at the end of June. In June, the laughing epidemic spread to Ramashenye girls' middle school, near [[Bukoba, Tanzania|Bukoba]], affecting 48 girls. Another outbreak occurred in Kanyangereka and two nearby boys schools were closed.<ref name=\"epidemic\"/>\n* June bug epidemic (1962) - The June bug epidemic serves as a classic example of [[hysterical contagion]]. In 1962 a mysterious disease broke out in a dressmaking department of a US textile factory. The symptoms included numbness, nausea, dizziness, and vomiting. Word of a bug in the factory that would bite its victims and cause them to develop the above symptoms quickly spread.<ref>Alan C. Kerckhoff & Kurt W. Back (1968) ''The June Bug: a study of hysterical contagion'', [[Appleton-Century-Crofts]]</ref> Soon 62 employees developed this mysterious illness, some of whom were hospitalized. The news media reported on the case. After research by company physicians and experts from the US Public Health Service Communicable Disease Center, it was concluded that the case was one of mass hysteria. While the researchers believed some workers were bitten by the bug, anxiety was probably the cause of the symptoms. No evidence was ever found for a bug which could cause the above flu-like symptoms, nor did all workers demonstrate bites.\n* Welsh, Louisiana (1962) - With students' sexual activity under close scrutiny by school officials, and following rumors of mandatory pregnancy tests, 21 girls and one boy in grades six to eleven were affected by seizures and other symptoms over six months.<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Blackburn, England (1965) - In October 1965 at a girls' school in [[Blackburn]], several girls complained of dizziness.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\">Moss, P. D. and C. P. McEvedy. \"An epidemic of overbreathing among schoolgirls.\" ''British Medical Journal'' 2(5525) (1966):1295\u20131300. Web. 17 Dec. 2009.</ref> Some fainted. Within a couple of hours, 85 girls from the school were rushed by ambulance to a nearby hospital after fainting. Symptoms included swooning, moaning, chattering of teeth, [[hyperpnea]], and [[Tetany (medical sign)|tetany]].<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> A medical analysis of the event about one year later found that outbreaks began among the 14-year-olds, but that the heaviest incidence moved to the youngest age groups.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> There was no evidence of pollution of food or air.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> The younger girls proved more susceptible, but disturbance was more severe and lasted longer in the older girls.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> Using the [[Eysenck Personality Questionnaire|Eysenck Personality Inventory]], those affected had higher scores for [[extroversion]] and [[neuroticism]].<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/> It was considered that the epidemic was hysterical, that a previous polio epidemic had rendered the population emotionally vulnerable, and that a three-hour parade, producing 20 faints on the day before the first outbreak, had been the specific trigger.<ref name=\"Moss, McEvedy\"/>\n* Mount Pleasant, Mississippi (1976) - School officials suspected drug use after 15 students fell to the ground writhing, but no drugs were found and hysteria is assumed to be the culprit. At one point, one third of the school's 900 students stayed home for fear of being \"hexed\".<ref name=\"mmis\"/>\n* Malaysia (1970s\u20131980s) - Mass hysteria occurred in Malaysia from the 1970s to the 1980s. It affected school-age girls and young women working in factories. The locals have explained this outbreak as \"[[Ethnic Malays#Religion|spirits]]\" having possessed the girls and young women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mass hysteria hits Malaysian school|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDP/is_2001_July_16/ai_77057810/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718083030/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDP/is_2001_July_16/ai_77057810/|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=Asian Economic News|date=July 16, 2001|agency=[[Kyodo News|Kyodo]]|location=Kuala Lumpur}}</ref><ref>http://smj.sma.org.sg/1604/1604smj11.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Ong|first=Aihwa|title=The Production of Possession: Spirits and the Multinational Corporation in Malaysia|journal=American Ethnologist|date=Feb 1988|volume=15|series=Medical Anthropology|issue=1|pages=28\u201342|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|location=University of California, Berkeley|jstor=645484|doi=10.1525/ae.1988.15.1.02a00030}}</ref>\n* Hollinwell incident (1980) - Around 300 people, mostly children, but including adults and babies, suddenly suffered fainting attacks, nausea and other symptoms. The [[Hollinwell incident]] remains one of the prime examples of mass hysteria.\n* The [[1983 West Bank fainting epidemic]]  was a series of incidents in March 1983 in which 943 Palestinian teenage girls, mostly schoolgirls, and a small number of [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] women soldiers fainted or complained of feeling nauseous in the West Bank. Israel was accused of using chemical warfare to sterilize West Bank women while IDF sources speculated that a toxic substance had been employed by Palestinian militants to stir up unrest,<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=More Schoolgirls in West Bank Fall Sick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/04/04/world/more-schoolgirls-in-west-bank-fall-sick.html|author = David K. Shipler|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date = April 4, 1983|accessdate=6 May 2011|location=Jerusalem}}</ref> but investigators concluded that even if some environmental irritant had originally been present, the wave of complaints was ultimately a product of mass hysteria. This conclusion was supported by a Palestinian health official, who said that while 20% of the early cases may have been caused by the inhalation of some kind of gas, the remaining 80% were [[Somatoform disorder|psychosomatic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ailing Schoolgirls|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,953801,00.html#ixzz1M8CldpGE|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=Time|date=Apr 18, 1983}}</ref>\n* [[Day-care sex-abuse hysteria]] was a [[moral panic]] that occurred primarily in the 1980s and early 1990s featuring charges against [[day care|day-care]] providers of several forms of [[child abuse]], including [[Satanic ritual abuse]].<ref name=pbs>{{cite web |first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Innocence Lost, The Plea. |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/innocence/etc/other.html |publisher=[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] |accessdate=2009-03-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=L |last=Miller |title=Parole Board recommends Amirault's commutation |url=http://www.truthinjustice.org/amirault.htm |quote=The Amiraults always insisted they were innocent, the victims of a sex-abuse hysteria that swept the country in the 1980s and questionable testimony from child witnesses. |agency=Associated Press |date=2001-07-06 |accessdate=2007-10-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104063907/http://truthinjustice.org/amirault.htm |archivedate=2007-11-04 }}</ref>\n* San Diego (1988) - The US Navy evacuated 600 men from barracks; 119 were sent to San Diego hospitals with complaints of breathing difficulty. No evidence of toxins, food poisoning, or any other cause was found.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-09-05/local/me-1019_1_navy-recruits|title=117 of Ill Recruits Returned to Base|date=September 5, 1988|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Kosovo student poisoning]], 1990 - Zoran Radovanovi\u0107, a professor in the Faculty of Medicine in Kuwait argues in an article for the European Journal of Epidemiology that the \"Kosovo Student Poisoning\" that affected at least four thousand, mostly ethnic Albanians, was a product of mass hysteria.\n* Belgium (June 1999) - Soft drink giant Coca-Cola withdrew 30 million units of its product from sale after more than a hundred people in Belgium and northern France complained of cramps, nausea and other problems after consuming the soft drinks. Testing found no evidence of tainted product and the incident was reported to be a panic, perhaps fueled by the discovery of [[Dioxin affair|dioxins in Belgian meat]], which had brought down the national government earlier that year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillner |first1=Luisa |title=A case of mass hysteria |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/1999/jul/06/healthandwellbeing.health |accessdate=24 February 2019 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |date=6 July 1999}}</ref>\n*Many UFO reports may be the result of mass hysteria https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/how-ufo-reports-change-with-technology-times-180968011/\n\n==2000s==\n\n* North Carolina (2002) - Ten girls developed seizures and other symptoms at a rural high school in North Carolina. Symptoms persisted for five months across various grade levels. Incidents tended to happen outside of class, with half of all incidents estimated to have occurred around lunch hour. Half of the affected were cheerleaders or former cheerleaders.<ref name=\"mmis2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pDLAgAAQBAJ|title=Mass Hysteria in Schools: A Worldwide History Since 1566|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"enddtomh\">{{cite web|url=http://roc.democratandchronicle.com/assets/pdf/A2185611224.pdf|title=Episodic Neurological Dysfunction Due to Mass Hysteria|date=February 24, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n* \"''Strawberries with Sugar'' virus\" (2006) - In May 2006, an outbreak of the so-dubbed [[Morangos com A\u00e7\u00facar Virus]] (Strawberries with Sugar virus) was reported in Portuguese schools, named after the popular teen girl's show ''[[Morangos com A\u00e7\u00facar]]'' (''Strawberries With Sugar''). 300 or more students at 14 schools reported similar symptoms to those experienced by the characters in a then recent episode where a life-threatening virus affected the school depicted in the show.<ref name=\"ibnlive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/teenagers-hit-by-soap-opera-virus/10909-13.html|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|title=Teenagers hit by soap opera virus|date=May 19, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2006-05/19/content_595035.htm|publisher=[[China Daily]]|title=Teens suffer soap opera virus|date=May 19, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref> Symptoms included rashes, difficulty breathing, and dizziness. The belief that there was a medical outbreak forced some schools to temporarily close. The Portuguese National Institute for Medical Emergency eventually dismissed the illness as mass hysteria.<ref name=\"ibnlive\" /><ref name=\"chinadaily\" />\n* Mexico City (2007) - In 2007 near Chalco, a working-class suburb of Mexico City, mass hysteria resulted in a massive outbreak of unusual symptoms suffered by adolescent female students (600) at Children's Village School, a Catholic boarding-school.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mysterious illness strikes teenage girls in Mexico|first=Elisabeth|last=Malkin|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 16, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/16/world/americas/16iht-mexico.3.5306132.html|accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zavala|first1=Nashyiela Loa|year=2010|title=The expulsion of evil and its return: An unconscious fantasy associated with a case of mass hysteria in adolescents|journal=[[International Journal of Psychoanalysis]] |volume=91 |issue=5 |pages=1157\u201378 |doi=10.1111/j.1745-8315.2010.00322.x |pmid=20955250}}</ref>  The afflicted students had difficulty walking and were feverish and nauseated.\n* Vinton, Virginia (2007) - An outbreak of twitching, headaches and dizziness affected at least nine girls and one teacher at William Byrd High School. The episode lasted for months amid other local public health scares.<ref name=\"mmis2\"/>\n* Afghanistan (2009\u2013) - Starting around 2009, a spate of apparent poisonings at girls' schools across Afghanistan began to be reported, with symptoms including dizziness, fainting, and vomiting. The [[United Nations]], [[World Health Organization]] and NATO's [[International Security Assistance Force]] carried out investigations of the incidents over multiple years, but never found any evidence of toxins or poisoning in the hundreds of blood, urine, and water samples they tested. The conclusion of the investigators was that the girls were suffering from [[mass psychogenic illness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/9376348/Poisonings-at-Afghan-girls-schools-likely-mass-hysteria-not-Taliban-says-report.html|title=Poisonings' at Afghan girls' schools likely mass hysteria \u2013 not Taliban, says report|date=4 July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newsweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/are-taliban-poisoning-afghan-schoolgirls-evidence-65587|title=Are the Taliban Poisoning Afghan Schoolgirls? The Evidence|date=9 July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Despite these findings, Afghan officials often blame the incidents on the [[Taliban]], accusing them of contaminating the school's water supply or using poison gas.<ref name=\"newsweek\"/>\n* Brunei (2010) - In April and May 2010, incidents of mass hysteria occurred at two all-girls secondary schools in [[Brunei]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bandial |first=Quratul-Ain |title=Mass hysteria: product of 'jinn' or anxiety? |url=http://news.brunei.fm/2010/05/13/mass-hysteria-product-of-jinn-or-anxiety/ |accessdate=9 May 2012 |newspaper=The Brunei Times |date=May 13, 2010 |location=BRUNEI-MUARA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422081110/http://news.brunei.fm/2010/05/13/mass-hysteria-product-of-jinn-or-anxiety/ |archivedate=22 April 2012 }}</ref> The most recent notable event happened on the 24 April 2014 in a public secondary school. The phenomenon caused a wave of panic among many parents, educators, and members of the community. Some of the students affected by the phenomenon claimed to have been possessed by spirits, or [[jinn]], displaying [[histrionic personality disorder|histrionic]] symptoms such as screaming, shaking, fainting, and crying.\n* LeRoy, New York (2011\u201312) - In late 2011, 12 high school girls developed [[Tourette syndrome|Tourette-like symptoms]]. Their school was tested for toxins, and all other factors for their symptoms were ruled out. The case, and some of the girls and their parents, gained national media attention. In January 2012, several more students and a 36-year-old adult female came forward with similar symptoms. They were all diagnosed with [[conversion disorder]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/12-girls-at-ny-high-school-develop-involuntary-tics-doc-says-its-mass-psychogenic-illness/2012/01/20/gIQA5k5bEQ_story.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123183938/http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/12-girls-at-ny-high-school-develop-involuntary-tics-doc-says-its-mass-psychogenic-illness/2012/01/20/gIQA5k5bEQ_story.html | archive-date=2012-01-23 | url-status=dead|title=12 girls at NY high school develop involuntary tics|work=Washington Post}} </ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McGowan|first=Kate|title=LeRoy Woman Discloses 'Conversion Disorder', Talks Exclusively to YNN|url=http://jamestown.ynn.com/content/top_stories/571923/leroy-woman-discloses--conversion-disorder---talks-exclusively-to-ynn/|accessdate=9 May 2012|newspaper=YNN|date=2012-01-29}}</ref>\n* Sri Lanka (2012) - From November 15\u201320, 2012, incidents of mass hysteria occurred at 15 schools in [[Sri Lanka]]. More than 1,900 school children of 15 schools in Sri Lanka and five teachers were treated for a range of symptoms that included skin rashes, vomiting, vertigo, and cough due to allergic reactions believed to be mass hysteria. It originated at the Jinaraja Balika Vidyala in Gampola, Central Province on November 15, 2012 when 1,100 students were admitted to hospital with a range of symptoms that included skin rashes, vomiting, vertigo and coughing. Later, authorities had to close down the school for 3 days. After that on November 16\u201319 there were more reports of students from other parts of the country showing similar symptoms.<ref>{{cite news|title= Sri Lanka Mass Hysteria at Schools |url=http://www.lankauniversity-news.com/2012/11/sri-lankamass-hysteria-cause-of-school.html}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2013}}\n* Charlie Charlie panic (2015) - Four teens in Tunja, Colombia were hospitalized, and several in the Dominican Republic were considered \"possessed by Satan\" after playing the [[Charlie Charlie Challenge]] viral game.<ref>{{cite news|title= 'Charlie Charlie' game summoning Mexican demon goes viral, causing damage real and fake |url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/lifestyle/2015/06/10/charlie-charlie-game-summoning-mexican-demon-goes-viral-causing-damage-real-and/}}</ref>\n* [[2016 clown sightings]] - Sightings of people in [[evil clown]] costumes in the United States, Canada, and 18 other countries were dismissed as a case of mass hysteria, stating that a [[Coulrophobia|fear of clowns]] (which is common in children and adults) may be an underlying cause.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/7/13191788/clown-attack-threats-2016-panic-hoax-debunked|title=The 2016 clown panic: 10 questions asked and answered|author=Angela Chen|date=7 October 2016|work=theverge.com|access-date=1 November 2016}}</ref> The website ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' likewise claimed that \"The Great Clown Panic of 2016 has been perpetuated by pretty much everyone except actual clowns.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/10/12/13122196/clown-panic-hoax-history|title=The great clown panic of 2016 is a hoax. But the terrifying side of clowns is real.|date=12 October 2016|access-date=3 November 2016|author=Aja Romano|work=vox.com}}</ref>\n* Emirates Flight 203, September 2018 - 106 of 521 passengers on a 14-hour flight from Dubai to New York reported symptoms including coughing, sneezing, fever, or vomiting. The pilot notified airport ground staff, and personnel from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] met and quarantined the plane in New York and evaluated passengers, 11 of whom were sent to the hospital. A few passengers on the \"flight from hell\" turned out to have common colds or flu, with the other passengers coming to the belief that they were also sick after observing those around them.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/carolinekee/sick-passengers-emirates-flight-dubai-nyc-quarantine A Flight From Dubai Carrying Dozens Of Sick Passengers Was Quarantined In New York]</ref><ref>[https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/on-the-media-2018-12-14 On the Media - Plague of Suspicion]</ref>\n*In August 2019 the BBC reported that schoolgirls at the [[Ketereh|Ketereh national secondary school]] (SMK Ketereh) in [[Kelantan]], [[Malaysia]], started screaming, with some claiming to have seen 'a face of pure evil'. Professor [[Simon Wessely]] a former president of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]] suggested it was a form of 'collective behaviour'. [[Robert Bartholomew]], a medical sociologist sugessted it was due to the stricter implementation of [[Sharia|Islamic law]] in the school. The school responded to the outbreak by cutting down the trees around the school, believing they were home to supernatural spirits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48850490|title=The mystery of screaming schoolgirls in Malaysia|last=Chen|first=Heather|date=11 August 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* Starehe Girls Centre, Kenya (October 2019) - 52 students were isolated with an unknown disease, showing symptoms of a high-pitched cough, sneezing and low-grade fever, a number that later rose to 68. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/2019-10-04-starehe-girls-students-suffering-from-mass-hysteria-health-ministry/|title=Starehe girls diagnosed with mass hysteria\n|last=Agutu|first=Nancy|date=4 October 2019|work=The Star|access-date=5 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> As the number rose, the school's administration shut the school down and instructed parents to pickup their daughters. Specimens collected from the affected students showed only two cases of rhinovirus, a virus that is the predominant cause of the common cold. After carrying out psychological assessments on the students, a team of mental health specialists dispatched by Kenya's Ministry of Health to the school concluded that the 'mysterious' disease was a case of mass hysteria.\n* Mass hysteria occured during the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-mass-panic-unlikely-pandemic/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== See Also==\n\n* [[Body-centred countertransference]]\n* [[Conversion disorder]]\n* [[Folie \u00e0 deux]] (from the French for \"a madness shared by two\")\n* [[Hysterical contagion]] \n* [[Psychochemical weaponry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bartholomew, Robert E. (2001). ''Little Green Men, Meowing Nuns and Head-hunting Panics: A Study of Mass Psychogenic Illnesses and Social Delusion''. McFarland.\n* Bartholomew, Robert E; [[Hilary Evans|Evans, Hilary]]. (2009). ''Outbreak! The Encyclopedia of Extraordinary Social Behavior''. Anomalist Books.\n* [[Amos Norton Craft|Craft, Amos Norton]]. (1881). [https://archive.org/details/EpidemicDelusions ''Epidemic Delusions: Containing an Expos\u00e9 of the Superstitions and Frauds which Underlie Some Ancient and Modern Delusions, Including Especial Reference to Modern Spiritualism'']. New York: Phillips & Hunt.\n* Fleischer, Jeff. (2011). ''The Latest Craze: A Short History of Mass Hysterias''. Fall River Press.\n* [[Charles Mackay (author)|Mackay, Charles]]. (1856 edition). ''[[Memoirs of Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds]]''. London, New York: G. Routledge and Sons.\n* Verma, S. K; Srivastava, D. K. (2003). [https://web.archive.org/web/20150627212301/http://indianjmedsci.org/article.asp?issn=0019-5359;year=2003;volume=57;issue=8;spage=355;epage=60;aulast=Verma ''A Study on Mass Hysteria (Monkey Men?) Victims In East Delhi'']. Indian Journal of Medical Sciences 57: 355-360.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://science.howstuffworks.com/life/inside-the-mind/human-brain/collective-hysteria.htm Six hundred girls in Mexico suffer from collective hysteria]\n* [http://www.lankauniversity-news.com/2012/11/sri-lankamass-hysteria-cause-of-school.html Sri Lanka Mass Hysteria ]\n* [http://skepdic.com/masshysteria.html Mass hysteria] - [[Skeptic's Dictionary]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021195040/http://www.csicop.org/si/show/mass_delusions_and_hysterias_highlights_from_the_past_millennium Mass Delusions and Hysterias: Highlights from the Past Millennium] - [[Skeptical Inquirer]]\n\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n{{Speculative fiction all}}\n{{World view}}\n\n[[Category:Mass hysteria| ]]\n[[Category:Group processes]]\n", "name_user": "ShockD", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_mass_hysteria_cases"}
{"title_page": "Key Resolve", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual command post exercise}}\n{{Expand Korean|\ud0a4 \ub9ac\uc878\ube0c|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Key Resolve''', previously known as '''Reception, Staging, Onward Movement, Integration''' ('''RSOI''') which was previously known as [[Team Spirit]] even earlier, is an annual [[Military_exercise#Command_Post_Exercise|command post exercise]] (CPX) held by [[United States Forces Korea]] with the [[Military of South Korea|Republic of Korea Armed Forces]]. It is conducted between February and April and focuses on [[United States Pacific Command]] [[OPLAN]]s that support the defense of [[South Korea]]. Additionally, US units are moved to Korea from other areas and they conduct maneuvers and gunnery exercises. ROK units also conduct maneuvers with some acting as the [[Opposing force]] (OPFOR). Since 2001, Key Resolve combined with the annual combined [[field training exercise]] (FTX) [[Foal Eagle]]. <ref name=\"Key Resolve U.S. Forces Korea 2009\">{{cite web | title= 'Key Resolve' begins in Korea | url= http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/03/10/18017-key-resolve-begins-in-korea/ | work=  U.S. Forces Korea | publisher= U.S. Army | date= March 10, 2009 | accessdate=2010-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Reception, Staging, Onward movement, and Integration | url= http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/rsoi.htm | work= Military \u2013 Operations | publisher= GlobalSecurity.org | date= October 23, 2007 | accessdate=2010-02-03}}</ref>\n\nDoctrinally, RSOI is detailed in [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625003049/http://www.transchool.eustis.army.mil/lic/FMs/fm100_17_3.pdf FM 100-17-3], the field manual for RSOI.\n\nThis exercise, like the [[Ulchi-Freedom Guardian]] (UFG) exercise, regularly leads to accusations by North Korea that it is a prelude to an invasion by the United States and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2917570|title=North strongly protests new Key Resolve joint exercises|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\n[[Japan]] supports the joint drills of South Korea and the US, considering it to be a deterrent power in the Asian-Pacific region.<ref name=\"joing drills begin\">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180401_08/|title=US-S.Korea joint drills begin|publisher=NHK World \u2013 Japan|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=6 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404073736/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180401_08/|archive-date=4 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit|North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit]] in February 2019, the [[United States Department of Defense]] announced that that United States and South Korea \"decided  to conclude the Key Resolve and [[Foal Eagle]] series of exercises\".<ref name=dod-20190302>{{cite press release |url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/1773294/readout-of-minister-of-national-defense-jeong-kyeong-doos-phone-call-with-actin/ |title=Readout of Minister of National Defense Jeong Kyeong-doo's Phone Call With Acting Secretary of Defense Patrick Shanahan |publisher=Department of Defense |date=2 March 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> They were replaced by the [[Dong Maeng]] joint military exercise in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea, US to replace massive springtime military drills with 'Dong Maeng' exercise |url= https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/south-korea-us-to-replace-massive-springtime-military-drills-with-dong-maeng-exercise |date=March 3, 2019| publisher=The Straights Times}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n* [https://www2.apan-info.net/apan/j7/Exercises/RSOI/tabid/155/Default.aspx Asian-Pacific Area Network]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2917570 North strongly protests new Key Resolve joint exercises], March 9, 2010, JoongAng Daily\n\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/rsoi.htm RSOI] - GlobalSecurity.org\n* Official photos: [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614626764992/ 2006], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614372491498/ 2007], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614123587608/ 2008], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614753814377/ 2009]\n\n[[Category:Military of South Korea]]\n[[Category:United States military in South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Military exercises involving the United States]]\n\n\n{{SouthKorea-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Annual command post exercise}}\n{{Expand Korean|\ud0a4 \ub9ac\uc878\ube0c|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Key Resolve''', previously known as '''Reception, Staging, Onward Movement, Integration''' ('''RSOI''') which was previously known as [[Team Spirit]] even earlier, is an annual [[Military_exercise#Command_Post_Exercise|command post exercise]] (CPX) held by [[United States Forces Korea]] with the [[Military of South Korea|Republic of Korea Armed Forces]]. It is conducted between February and April and focuses on [[United States Pacific Command]] [[OPLAN]]s that support the defense of [[South Korea]]. Additionally, US units are moved to Korea from other areas and they conduct maneuvers and gunnery exercises. ROK units also conduct maneuvers with some acting as the [[Opposing force]] (OPFOR). Since 2001, Key Resolve combined with the annual combined [[field training exercise]] (FTX) [[Foal Eagle]]. <ref name=\"Key Resolve U.S. Forces Korea 2009\">{{cite web | title= 'Key Resolve' begins in Korea | url= http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/03/10/18017-key-resolve-begins-in-korea/ | work=  U.S. Forces Korea | publisher= U.S. Army | date= March 10, 2009 | accessdate=2010-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Reception, Staging, Onward movement, and Integration | url= http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/rsoi.htm | work= Military - Operations | publisher= GlobalSecurity.org | date= October 23, 2007 | accessdate=2010-02-03}}</ref>\n\nDoctrinally, RSOI is detailed in [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625003049/http://www.transchool.eustis.army.mil/lic/FMs/fm100_17_3.pdf FM 100-17-3], the field manual for RSOI.\n\nThis exercise, like the [[Ulchi-Freedom Guardian]] (UFG) exercise, regularly leads to accusations by North Korea that it is a prelude to an invasion by the United States and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2917570|title=North strongly protests new Key Resolve joint exercises|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\n[[Japan]] supports the joint drills of South Korea and the USA, considering it to be a deterrent power in the Asian-Pacific region.<ref name=\"joing drills begin\">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180401_08/|title=US-S.Korea joint drills begin|publisher=NHK World - Japan|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=6 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404073736/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180401_08/|archive-date=4 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit|North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit]] in February 2019, the [[United States Department of Defense]] announced that that United States and South Korea \"decided  to conclude the Key Resolve and [[Foal Eagle]] series of exercises\".<ref name=dod-20190302>{{cite press release |url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/1773294/readout-of-minister-of-national-defense-jeong-kyeong-doos-phone-call-with-actin/ |title=Readout of Minister of National Defense Jeong Kyeong-doo's Phone Call With Acting Secretary of Defense Patrick Shanahan |publisher=Department of Defense |date=2 March 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> They were replaced by the [[Dong Maeng]] joint military exercise in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea, US to replace massive springtime military drills with 'Dong Maeng' exercise |url= https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/south-korea-us-to-replace-massive-springtime-military-drills-with-dong-maeng-exercise |date=March 3, 2019| publisher=The Straights Times}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n* [https://www2.apan-info.net/apan/j7/Exercises/RSOI/tabid/155/Default.aspx Asian-Pacific Area Network]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2917570 North strongly protests new Key Resolve joint exercises], March 9, 2010, JoongAng Daily\n\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/rsoi.htm RSOI] - GlobalSecurity.org\n* Official photos: [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614626764992/ 2006], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614372491498/ 2007], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614123587608/ 2008], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/unc-cfc-usfk/sets/72157614753814377/ 2009]\n\n[[Category:Military of South Korea]]\n[[Category:United States military in South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Military exercises involving the United States]]\n\n\n{{SouthKorea-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Resolve"}
{"title_page": "Lew Hoad", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian tennis player}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                        = Lew Hoad\n|image                       = Lew Hoad 1954 Davis Cup.jpg\n|caption                     = Lew Hoad at Davis Cup\n|fullname                    = Lewis Alan Hoad\n|country                     = {{AUS}}\n|residence                   = \n|birth_date                  = {{birth date|df=yes|1934|11|23}}\n|birth_place                 = [[Glebe, New South Wales|Glebe]], Australia\n|death_date                  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1994|07|03|1934|11|23}}\n|death_place                 = [[Fuengirola]], Spain\n|height                      = {{height|m=1.79}} \n|college                     = \n|turnedpro                   = 1957<small> (amateur tour from 1950)</small>\n|retired                     = 1972\n|plays                       = Right-handed (one-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney            = \n|tennishofyear               = 1980\n|tennishofid                 = lew-hoad\n|website                     = \n|singlesrecord               = 824\u2013503 (62.1%) <ref name=\"Lew Hoad: Career match record\">{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n|singlestitles               = 51 <ref name=\"Lew Hoad: Career match record\">{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n|highestsinglesranking       = No. '''1''' (1956<small>, [[Lance Tingay]]</small>)<ref name=\"USLTAEncyclopedia\">United States Lawn Tennis Association (1972). ''Official Encyclopedia of Tennis'' (First Edition), p. 426.</ref>\n|AustralianOpenresult        = '''W''' ([[1956 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]])\n|FrenchOpenresult            = '''W''' ([[1956 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]])\n|Wimbledonresult             = '''W''' ([[1956 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]], [[1957 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1957]])\n|USOpenresult                = F ([[1956 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]])\n|Promajors                   = yes\n|USProresult                 = F ([[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1958|1958]], [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1959|1959]])\n|WembleyProresult            = F ([[Wembley Championship#1961|1961]], [[Wembley Championship#1962|1962]], [[Wembley Championship#1963|1963]])\n|FrenchProresult             = F ([[French Pro Championship#1958|1958]], [[French Pro Championship#1960|1960]])\n|TOCresult                   = '''W''' ([[Tournament of Champions (tennis)|1959 Forest Hills, 1958 Kooyong]])\n|doublesrecord               = \n|doublestitles               = \n|highestdoublesranking       = \n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = '''W''' (1953, 1956, 1957)\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult     = '''W''' (1953)\n|WimbledonDoublesresult      = '''W''' ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles|1953]], [[1955 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles|1955]], [[1956 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles|1956]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult         = '''W''' (1956)\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult   = F (1955)\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult       = '''W''' (1954)\n|WimbledonMixedresult        = SF ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Mixed Doubles|1953]], [[1954 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Mixed Doubles|1954]], [[1955 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Mixed Doubles|1955]])\n|USOpenMixedresult           = F (1952, 1956)\n|Team                        = yes\n|DavisCupresult              = '''W''' ([[1952 Davis Cup|1952]], [[1953 Davis Cup|1953]], [[1955 Davis Cup|1955]], [[1956 Davis Cup|1956]])\n}}\n\n'''Lewis Alan Hoad''' (23 November 1934 \u2013 3 July 1994) was an Australian [[World number 1 male tennis player rankings|world No. 1]] [[tennis player]] whose career lasted from the early 1950s until the early 1970s.\n\nHoad won four [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournaments as an amateur (Australian, French and twice Wimbledon). He was a member of the [[Australia Davis Cup team|Australian team]] that won the [[Davis Cup]] four times between 1952 and 1956. Hoad turned professional in July 1957 and won the [[Tournament of Champions (tennis)|Forest Hills Tournament of Champions]] event in 1959. He also won the Ampol Tournament of Champions at Kooyong in 1958, one of the richest tournaments of the era. He won the Ampol Open Trophy world series in 1959\u20131960. During his career his main competitors were his longtime amateur tennis teammate [[Ken Rosewall]] and, throughout his professional career, [[Pancho Gonzales]].\n\nHoad was ranked in the world top ten for amateurs from 1952 until 1957, reaching the world No. 1 spot in 1956. He was ranked the world No. 1 professional in Kramer's official 1959\u20131960 Ampol ranking of all the contract professionals. He was ranked the world No. 1 tennis player, professional or amateur, for 1962 in a poll of 85 U.S. sports editors. \n\nSerious back problems plagued Hoad throughout his career, probably caused by a weight-lifting exercise he devised in 1954, particularly after he turned professional, and led to his effective retirement from tennis in 1967 although he made sporadic comebacks, enticed by the advent of the open era in 1968.\n\nIn his autobiography, [[Jack Kramer]], the professional tennis promoter and former player, rated Hoad as one of the 21 best players of all time.{{efn|name=kramer|Kramer considered the best player ever to have been either [[Don Budge]] (for consistent play) or [[Ellsworth Vines]] (at the height of his game). The next four best were, chronologically, [[Bill Tilden]], [[Fred Perry]], [[Bobby Riggs]], and [[Pancho Gonzales]]. After these six came the \"second echelon\" of [[Rod Laver]], Lew Hoad, [[Ken Rosewall]], [[Gottfried von Cramm]], [[Ted Schroeder]], [[Jack Crawford (tennis)|Jack Crawford]], [[Pancho Segura]], [[Frank Sedgman]], [[Tony Trabert]], [[John Newcombe]], [[Arthur Ashe]], [[Stan Smith]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Borg]], and [[Jimmy Connors]]. He felt unable to rank [[Henri Cochet]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Lacoste]] accurately but felt they were among the very best.}} [[Rod Laver]] in 2012 rated Hoad as the greatest player of the \"past champions\" era of tennis and stated that power, volleying and explosiveness were his strengths.\n\nFollowing his retirement in 1972, Hoad and his wife [[Jenny Staley Hoad|Jenny]] operated a tennis resort, ''Lew Hoad's Campo de Tenis'' in [[Fuengirola]], Spain, near M\u00e1laga. Hoad died of leukemia on 3 July 1994.\n\n==Early life and career==\n[[Image:Australian tennis player Lewis Hoad.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Lewis Hoad at age 15 competing at Kooyong in Inter State Tennis in 1949.]]\nLewis Hoad{{efn|name=actor|Lewis Hoad was named after the American actor [[Lewis Stone]].{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=3|ps=}}}} was born on 23 November 1934, in the working-class Sydney inner suburb of [[Glebe, New South Wales|Glebe]], the eldest of three sons of tramway electrician Alan Hoad and his wife Ailsa Lyle Burbury.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=3|ps=}} Hoad started playing tennis at age five with a racket gifted by a local social club.{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|pp=105,106|ps=}} As a young child, he would wake up at 5 a.m. and hit tennis balls against a wall and garage door until the neighbours complained, and he was allowed to practice on the courts of the Hereford Tennis Club behind the house.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|pp=3,4|ps=}}{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=106|ps=}} At age 10 he competed in the seaside tournament at [[Manly, New South Wales|Manly]] in the under 16 category.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17933284 |title=School for Tennis Juniors. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 December 1944 |accessdate=14 June 2014 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn his youth, he often played with [[Ken Rosewall]], and they became known as the Sydney \"twins\", although they had very different physiques, personalities and playing styles. Their first match was in their early teens and was played as an opener of an exhibition match between Australia and America. Rosewall won 6\u20130, 6\u20130.{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=107|ps=}} Hoad built up great physical strength, especially in his hands and arms, by training at a police boys' club, where he made a name as a boxer. Hoad was about 12 when he was introduced to [[Adrian Quist]], a former Australian tennis champion and then general manager of the [[Dunlop Sport|Dunlop]] sports goods company. Quist played a couple of sets with Hoad and was impressed by his natural ability. When Hoad was 14 he left school and joined the Dunlop payroll, following the pattern of that 'shamateur' era when most of Australia's brightest tennis prospects were employed by sporting goods companies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Lew Hoad|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lew-hoad-1411724.html|publisher=The Independent|date=5 July 1994}}</ref>\n\nHoad had just turned 15 when he and Rosewall were selected to play for [[New South Wales]] in an interstate contest against [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18128860 |title=Rosewall, Hoad in state team. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=25 November 1949 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In November 1949, Hoad won the junior title at the New South Wales Championships, and the same weekend, he also competed in the final of the junior [[table tennis]] championship in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48607374 |title=N.S.W. Tennis Titles. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=26 November 1949  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18472523 |title=Table Tennis. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=27 November 1949  |page=12 Section: Sporting Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\n\n===Amateur career: 1951\u20131957===\n\n;1951\nHoad's first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournament appearance was at the [[1951 Australian Championships]] held in January at the White City Tennis Club in Sydney. He won his first match against [[Ron McKenzie (tennis)|Ronald McKenzie]] in straight sets but lost in the following round to defending champion [[Frank Sedgman]].<ref name=ausopen>{{cite web|title=Australian Open players results archive \u2013 Lew Hoad|url=http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/players/10641.html|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref> It was the only Grand Slam tournament he played that year.\n\n;1952\nIn 1952, he reached the third round of the [[1951 Australian Championships|Australian Championships]], played in Adelaide, and in April, he was selected by the [[Tennis Australia|Australasian Lawn Tennis Association]] as member of the team to play in overseas tournaments.{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=109|ps=}} In May, before departing to Europe, he won the singles title at the [[Australian Hard Court Championships|Australian Hardcourt Championships]] after a five-set win in the final against Rosewall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18505117 |title=Hoad Narrowly Beats Rosewall. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=4 May 1952 |page=5 Section: Sports Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad, who had never played a tournament on clay courts, received a walkover in the first round of the [[1952 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]] and lost in straight sets to sixth-seeded and 1947 and 1951 finalist [[Eric Sturgess]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article133183387 |title=3 Australians Beaten In Paris Tennis. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |date=23 May 1952  |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=109|ps=}} In only their second appearance as a doubles team at a Grand Slam event, Hoad and Rosewall reached the French semifinal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96514734 |title=French Cheer Hoad, Rosewall After Brilliant Win. |newspaper=[[The Northern Star]] |location=Lismore, NSW |date=31 May 1952 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad subsequently played the Belgian tennis championships in Brussels in early June and reached the quarterfinal in which he was outclassed by [[Budge Patty]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47417467 |title=Rosewall, Hoad Beaten In Belgian Tennis. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=7 June 1952  |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nHoad's first entry at the [[grass court]] [[Queen's Club Championship]] in June 1952 ended in the quarterfinal against countryman and eventual champion Frank Sedgman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23184880 |title=Australian final likely in tennis. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=21 June 1952 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A week later, he played his first match at the [[Wimbledon Championships]] defeating [[Beppe Merlo]] in a nervous and unimpressive five-set encounter.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23191788 |title=Italian star fights back, but \u2014 Hoad lazes way to singles win. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=25 June 1952 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|pp=109, 110|ps=}} Wins against Rolando del Bello and [[Alfred Huber (tennis)|Freddie Huber]] were followed by a fourth round loss against second-seeded and eventual finalist [[Jaroslav Drobn\u00fd]].{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=110|ps=}} Hoad and Rosewall caused an upset when they defeated second-seeded [[Gardnar Mulloy]] and [[Dick Savitt]] in the third round of the doubles event in a run that ended in the semifinal against [[Vic Seixas]] and Eric Sturgess.{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|pp=110, 111|ps=}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96517702 |title=Shock defeat by Hoad and Rosewall of top American doubles pair. |newspaper=[[The Northern Star]] |location=Lismore, NSW |date=30 June 1952  |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57105860 |title=Rosewalll. Hoad make history. |newspaper=[[The Morning Bulletin]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=30 June 1952 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter a semifinal result at the Swedish championships in July, and an exhibition between Australia and West Germany, Hoad and the Australian team traveled to the United States under the guidance of coach [[Harry Hopman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27099128 |title=Rose Narrowly Beats Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=14 July 1952 |page=17 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61212655 |title=DAVIS CUP MEN REACH N. YORK. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=30 July 1952 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> As a preparation for his first [[1952 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] he played the Meadow Club Invitational (Southampton), [[Eastern Grass Court Championships]] (South Orange), and Newport Invitational before teaming up with Rosewall to reach the semifinal of the U.S. National Doubles Championships in [[Brookline, Massachusetts|Brookline]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27103199 |title=Hoad out in first round. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=6 August 1952 |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122034249 |title=Rose beaten by Seixas. |newspaper=[[The Queensland Times]]  |date=16 August 1952  |page=3 Edition: Daily |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50519546 |title=3 Australians in tennis final. |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |date=25 August 1952 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was the eighth seeded foreign player at the U.S. Championships.{{efn|name=seeding|The U.S. Championships used separate seeding lists for U.S. and foreign players between 1927, the first year seeding were used, and 1956.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18280890 |title=Sedgman Hits At Split Seeds. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=9 September 1952  |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61215739 |title=Tennis seedings. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=28 August 1952 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He won four matches to reach his first Grand Slam quarterfinal but due in part to making 64 errors could not overcome his countryman Sedgman who would win the tournament without losing a set.{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=111|ps=}}<ref name=talbert>{{cite book|last=Talbert|first=Bill|title=Tennis Observed|year=1967|publisher=Barre Publishers|location=Boston|page=127|oclc=172306}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61216825 |title=Rosewall, Hoad eliminated in U.S. title games. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=6 September 1952 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> With [[Thelma Coyne Long]] he reached the final of the mixed doubles event, the first Grand Slam final of his career, but they lost in straight sets to [[Doris Hart]] and Frank Sedgman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138571108 |title=Sedgman and Doris Hart win mixed doubles. |newspaper=[[Cootamundra Herald]] |location=NSW |date=9 September 1952 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> An early loss at the [[Pacific Southwest Championships]] in September concluded his first overseas tour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2864262 |title=Hoad beaten in Pacific Championships. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=16 September 1952  |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In September, he was jointly ranked No. 10 in the world for 1952 with Rosewall by [[Lance Tingay]] of ''The Daily Telegraph''.<ref name=collins>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Bud|title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis|year=2010|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=[New York]|isbn=978-0942257700|pages=715, 717\u2013 718, 754|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article194579346 |title=Australians head tennis rankings |newspaper=[[Daily Examiner]] |date=17 September 1952 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;1953\n[[File:Lew Hoad 1953.jpg|thumb|250px|Lew Hoad in 1953]]\nHoad started 1953 poorly in the singles with a second-round exit against [[Clive Wilderspin]] at the [[1953 Australian Championships|Australian Championships]] in Melbourne after playing an uncharacteristic baseline game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18504560 |title=Hoad Defeated By Unseeded W. Australian. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=11 January 1953  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18353380 |title=Instructions beat Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=12 January 1953  |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He was more successful in doubles where he and Rosewall became the youngest team to win the [[List of Australian Open men's doubles champions|Australian doubles]] title after a victory in the final against [[Mervyn Rose]] and [[Don Candy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27130798 |title=Rosewall, Hoad take doubles title. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=17 January 1953 |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In March, Hoad successfully defended his singles title at the Australian Hardcourt Championships, defeating Rosewall in a five set semifinal, and 34-year-old [[John Bromwich]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18502363 |title=Hoad Proves Too Strong For Bromwich In Final. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=15 March 1953 |page=6 Section: Sports Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the semifinal, he survived six matchpoints against Rosewall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42766939 |title=Brilliant tennis by Lewis Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=14 March 1953 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118400435 |title=Hoad Saved Six Match Points. |newspaper=[[The Queensland Times]]  |date=13 March 1953 |page=3 Edition: Daily |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Two weeks later, Hoad lost the final of the N.S.W. Hardcourt Championships against Mervyn Rose.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134822729 |title=Rose in first major win. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |date=24 March 1953  |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad's second overseas tour started in late April, and after an exhibition in Cairo at the Gezira Sporting Club, he entered the [[Italian Open (tennis)|Italian Championships]] in Rome.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132607463 |title=Austn. tennis stars to play in Cair. |newspaper=[[The Dubbo Liberal and Macquarie Advocate]] |location=NSW |date=30 April 1953  |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18510292 |title=Australians Should Do Well On Tennis Tour. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=26 April 1953 |page=11 Section: Sporting Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He reached the final, losing to Drobn\u00fd in straight sets but won the doubles title with Rosewall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27170292 |title=Hoad trounced by Drobny in singles. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=13 May 1953  |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the [[1953 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]] in May, Hoad was seeded fourth and made it to the quarterfinals in which he lost to [[Vic Seixas]] due to overhitting and an unreliable serve.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75736356 |title=Tennis World:. |newspaper=[[The Mirror (Western Australia)|The Mirror]] |location=Perth |date=16 May 1953 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27167095 |title=Hoad overwhelmed by Seixas in three sets. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=28 May 1953 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad and Rosewall followed up their Australian title with a win at the French Championships after a three-set win in the final against countrymen Rose and Wilderspin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18369304 |title=Rosewall And Hoad Win Doubles Title In Three Easy Sets. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=1 June 1953 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In June Hoad's attacking serve-and-volley game proved too good for Wimbledon favorite Rosewall in the final of the Queen's Club Championship and he won the tournament without losing a set.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69477450 |title=Hoad is too good for Rosewall. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=22 June 1953 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article145491522 |title=Another Hoad-Rosewall duel. |newspaper=[[The Daily Advertiser (Wagga Wagga)|Daily Advertiser]] |location=Wagga Wagga, NSW |date=22 June 1953  |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At Wimbledon, Hoad was seeded sixth, and as at the French, Vic Seixas defeated him in the quarterfinal, this time in a close five-set match that ended on a Hoad double fault.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69476681 |title=Rosewall seeded Wimbledon No. 1. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=17 June 1953 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69478690 |title=Hoad, Rosewall lose singles matches. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=30 June 1953 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In an all-Australian doubles final Hoad and Rosewall defeated Hartwig and Rose to win their third Grand Slam doubles title of the year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61084374 |title=Rosewall and Hoad Win Doubles. |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Tasmania)|The Examiner]] |location=Launceston, Tas. |date=6 July 1953 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad lost to [[Enrique Morea]] in the final of the Dutch Championships in mid July.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134208544 |title=Morea beats Lew Hoad. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 July 1953 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He won his first title on U.S. soil in [[South Orange]] at the [[Eastern Grass Court Championships]] in mid August, defeating compatriot [[Rex Hartwig]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48260977 |title=Hoad Stops Hartwig's Winning Run. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=11 August 1953  |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134208044 |title=Hoad Trounces Hartwig |newspaper=News |volume=61 |issue=9,360 |location=South Australia |date=10 August 1953 |accessdate=15 October 2016 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the semifinal against Rosewall, he pulled a back muscle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18385537 |title=Hoad injures muscle in back. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=11 August 1953 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad and Rosewall's hopes of winning the doubles Grand Slam, two years after fellow Australians [[Ken McGregor]] and Frank Sedgman had first achieved that feat, were dashed when they lost surprisingly in the third round of the U.S. Doubles Championships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100389509 |title=Hoad And Rosewall Down To U.S. Pair. |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=NSW |date=21 August 1953 |page=3|edition=Daily and Evening |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAs the second-seeded foreign player, Hoad was one of the favorites for the singles title at the [[1953 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|U.S. Championships]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27165702 |title=Australians top U.S. seedings. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=27 August 1953  |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He won four matches to reach the semifinal where for the third time in 1953 he lost in a Grand Slam event to Vic Seixas.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130777857 |title=Rosewall, Hoad failL. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=7 September 1953  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Following his defeat, and that of Rosewall in the other semifinal, there was criticism in the press that both 18-year-old players were physically and mentally worn out due to the intensive schedule imposed by coach Harry Hopman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18383562 |title=Strong attack on Hopman. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=9 September 1953 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48921437 |title='Hopman Ruined Players' Morale'. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=11 September 1953 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In September, Seixas again beat Hoad, this time in the semifinal of the Pacific Southwest Championships in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48933520 |title=Rosewall Beats Trabert. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=21 September 1953 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was rested a few weeks upon his return to Australia and then entered the Queensland Championships in early November where he won the singles title in a 41-minute final against Hartwig.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131248258 |title=Win to Hoad in straight sets. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=7 November 1953 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23319376 |title=Hoad invincible in smashing singles victory. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=9 November 1953 |page=17 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Two weeks later, Hoad won the N.S.W. Championships after a four-set victory in the final over Rosewall in front of a 10,000 Sydney crowd but had trouble with a sore right elbow.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article58877927 |title=Hoad, 18, youngest player to win NSW singles title. |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=21 November 1953  |page=4 Section: SPORTS SECTION |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18397547 |title=Heat treatments for Hoads elbow. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=23 November 1953 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18397369 |title=Hoad Has Sore Elbow. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=21 November 1953  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> His good form continued in early December at the Victorian Championships when he again defeated Rosewall in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article58876086 |title=Hoad beats Rosewall; both in great form. |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=5 December 1953  |page=42 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The much anticipated [[1953 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]] challenge round match against defendants United States took place at the Melbourne [[Kooyong Stadium]] in late December. Surprisingly Hartwig was selected to partner Hoad in the doubles instead of Rosewall, a decision widely criticized in the press.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223423316 |title=Australia's Cup doubles pairing roasted overseas |newspaper=[[Lithgow Mercury]] |date=30 December 1953 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the opening singles matches, Hoad defeated Seixas, his nemesis that season, in straight sets, while Trabert defeated Rosewall, also in straight sets. Hoad and Hartwig lost the doubles match against Seixas and Trabert and Australia trailed 1\u20132 at the start of the final day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132597738 |title=Selectors should resign says Davis Cup critic. |newspaper=[[The Dubbo Liberal and Macquarie Advocate]] |location=NSW |date=30 December 1953  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100391794 |title=Tennis Critics Hit at \"Boner\". |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=NSW |date=30 December 1953 |page=3|edition=Daily and Evening |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2913849 |title=The Cup selectors' \"Mistake\". |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=30 December 1953 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18402731 |title=\"Biggest tragedy of tennis\". |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=30 December 1953 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad is remembered for his match as a 19-year-old amateur against the United States champion [[Tony Trabert]]. In a hard-fought match in front of a 17,000 crowd, Hoad defeated Trabert in five sets to help his country retain the Cup.{{efn|name=rosewall|Ken Rosewall won the deciding rubber, played on the next day due to rain, against Vic Seixas in three straight sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131241965 |title=Rosewall's great battle. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=31 December 1953 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47584376 |title=\"Best Tennis I Have Ever Seen\". |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=31 December 1953 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|pp=102\u2013104, 113, 114|ps=}} It was seen as one of the best Davis Cup matches in history.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23305909 |title='Topped all games'. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=31 December 1953 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=105|ps=}} Directly following the final, Hoad received his call-up papers for [[Conscription in Australia#National Service in the 1950s|National Service]].{{sfnp|Davidson|1970|p=114|ps=}} Hoad was ranked No. 5 in the world for the year according to Lance Tingay.{{efn|name=tingay1953|Tingay's ratings were made in early September immediately after the U.S. Championships, and before the Davis Cup finals in December, where Hoad defeated Trabert.}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69489881 |title=Trabert is No. 1 tennis player |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Australia)]] |date=16 September 1953  |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=collins/> Hoad won 10 tournaments in 1953 and was 6 wins and 0 losses against Rosewall that year.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n;1954\n\n[[File:Ken Rosewall Lew Hoad 1954 Davis Cup.jpeg|thumb|Ken Rosewall (l) and Lew Hoad (r) at the [[1954 Davis Cup]] challenge-round match against the US at [[White City Stadium|White City]], Sydney.]]\nIn January, Hoad played just one tournament before entering his National Service training. At the [[South Australian Championships]] in Adelaide he reached the final but sub-par play led to a straight-sets defeat to Trabert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article58094803 |title=Hoad far below best; volleying poor, backhand wilted. |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=9 January 1954 |page=7 Section: Sports section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> On 13 January, Hoad joined the 13th National Service Training battalion in [[Ingleburn, New South Wales|Ingleburn]] for a period of 98 days and commented that ''\"It will be a welcome break from tennis\"''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69882269 |title=Lew Hoad in camp. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=14 January 1954  |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> As a consequence, Hoad was unable to participate in the [[1954 Australian Championships|Australian Championships]]. At the end of February, Hoad received a leave from service to play for the Australian team in the third test match against South Africa in front of the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]]. He played a singles match, a doubles match with Rosewall and a mixed-doubles match with his girlfriend [[Jenny Staley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26593422 |title=Africa leads in Test. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=27 February 1954  |page=48 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26593556 |title=Africa shocks Aussie stars in tennis Test. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=28 February 1954 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> When Hoad returned to service, he was bitten by a spider while on maneuvers which caused him to become ill and hospitalized him for ten days.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130870595 |title=Hoad's stay in hospital extended. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=5 March 1954 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He spent two days in coma which was not made public.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=22|ps=}}\n\nWhile he was in service, Hoad devised a weight-lifting exercise, doing push-ups with round 50 lb. weights placed on his back, which Hoad later believed probably initiated his back trouble.<ref>Clifford Hoad, \"Kings of the Sun\"</ref> Hoad left the National Service at the end of April and his third overseas tour with an Australian team started on 5 May.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96266821 |title=Australians Leave For Tour. |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Tasmania)|The Examiner]] |location=Launceston, Tas. |date=6 May 1954 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> For the first time in his career, Hoad was the top-seeded player at a Grand Slam tournament when he entered the [[1954 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]] but he failed to live up to it when he lost in the fourth round to 41-year-old [[Gardnar Mulloy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96390951 |title=Hoad Seeded No. 1 in France. |newspaper=[[The Northern Star]] |location=Lismore, NSW |date=17 May 1954 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84598242 |title=Hoad out of French tournament. |newspaper=[[The Singleton Argus]] |location=NSW |date=24 May 1954 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad reached the doubles final with Rosewall but the pair were soundly beaten by Seixas and Trabert in a 56-minute final. Partnering [[Maureen Connolly]], who had won the women's singles title, Hoad won the mixed-doubles event after a win in the final against [[Jacqueline Patorni]] and [[Rex Hartwig]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131395496 |title=Australians eclipsed. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=31 May 1954 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In June, Hoad overcame countryman Rose in the final of the Queen's Club Championship to successfully defend his 1953 singles title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59690815 |title=Hoad's second successive Queen's Club singles win. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Sunday Times]] |location=Perth |date=20 June 1954  |page=8 Edition: Country edition, Section: Sporting Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was one of the favorites for the [[1954 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]] and was seeded second behind Trabert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69976463 |title=Trabert seeded No. 1 for Wimbledon: Hoad second. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=16 June 1954 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the fourth round, Hoad avenged his loss to Mulloy at the French Championships, defeating him in four sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48106135 |title=Hood Avenges Defeat In French Championship. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=28 June 1954 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the quarterfinal the powerful service and excellent returns of 33-year-old Jaroslav Drobn\u00fd proved too much for Hoad and he was beaten in straight sets within the hour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69978489 |title=Rosewall only Australian not beaten at Wimbledon. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=29 June 1954 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad and Rosewall were unable to defend their Wimbledon doubles title after losing in fives sets in the semifinal to Seixas and Trabert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69853286 |title=U.S. pair beats Hoad-Rosewall. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=2 July 1954 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A surprise loss against [[Roger Becker]] in the semifinal at the Midlands Counties Championships in Birmingham was followed in mid-July by winning the singles title at the [[Swiss Open (tennis)|Swiss Championships]] in Gstaad.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134755237 |title=Hoad beaten in UK tennis. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=10 July 1954  |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27215021 |title=Hoad too strong for Fraser. |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tas. |date=20 July 1954  |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> As in the previous year, Hoad met Rosewall in the [[Eastern Grass Court Championships]] in August, this time in the final, and again the titleholder was victorious, overpowering Rosewall to win the singles title in three straight sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134654652 |title=Eastern Title Win To L. Hoad. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |date=10 August 1954  |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] in mid August, Hoad was beaten by 17-year-old compatriot [[Roy Emerson]] who won the deciding set 8\u20136.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103499346 |title=Hoad Down To Junior. |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=NSW |date=13 August 1954 |page=3|edition=Daily and Evening |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18430366 |title=Emerson's Victory Is Praised. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=14 August 1954 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> For the third time in 1954, Seixas and Trabert defeated Hoad and Rosewall at a Grand Slam doubles event, winning the U.S. Doubles Championships in Brookline.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131253523 |title=Seixas and Trabert win U.S. doubles. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 August 1954 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n[[File:Lew Hoad 1954 Kooyong.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Lew Hoad at [[Kooyong Stadium|Kooyong]] in 1954]] \nHoad, seeded first among the foreign players at the [[1954 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|U.S. Championships]], failed to live up to his seeding when he lost to [[Ham Richardson]] in a five-set quarterfinal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130985870 |title=Hoad downed in five sets by Richardson. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=4 September 1954 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article81665161 |title=Trabert, Hoad Classed No. 1. |newspaper=[[The Northern Miner (Queensland)|The Northern Miner]] |location=Charters Towers, Qld. |date=26 August 1954 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> His lackluster form continued when he was defeated by unseeded [[Luis Ayala (tennis)|Luis Ayala]] in the quarterfinal of the Pacific Southwest Championships in mid-September.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134087011 |title=Hoad, Rosewall Lose In Singles. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |date=20 September 1954 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> After returning to Australia at the end of September, Hoad scheduled extra practice to work on his serve and volley but subsequently lost to [[Don Candy]] in the semifinal of the Sydney Metropolitan Championships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131212231 |title=Hoad keen to regain form. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=2 October 1954 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18446419 |title=Hoad lethargic in semi-final defeat. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=14 October 1954 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In early November, matters briefly improved as he consolidated the Queensland title in Brisbane. In the final, he overcame a sunstroke and the loss of sets three and four by 0\u20136 to defeat Hartwig in five sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50613583 |title=Hoad takes title. |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |date=8 November 1954 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In mid-November, he was upset by veteran [[John Bromwich]] who better exploited the windy conditions in the quarterfinal of the N.S.W. Championships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50622279 |title=Hoad's form worst for year. |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |date=17 November 1954  |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50610467 |title=Hopman: not worried over Hoad's defeat. |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |date=18 November 1954 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the Victorian Championships, the last significant tournament before the Davis Cup Challenge Round, Hoad was defeated in straight sets in the semifinal by Seixas. As in the previous match against [[Sven Davidson]] he showed such poor form and at times an apparent lack of interest that he was jeered by the crowd and several left after he smashed a ball into the stands.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=26,27|ps=}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18453564 |title=Quist's advice on Hoad: \"Must leave him alone\". |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=2 December 1954 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23453632 |title='No solution at present,' says Hopman. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=3 December 1954  |page=32 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The [[1954 Davis Cup]] Challenge Round was played on 27\u201329 December on the grass courts at the [[White City Stadium (Sydney)|White City Stadium]] in Sydney between title holders Australia and the United States. Hoad played the first rubber, in front of a record crowd of 25,000, which he lost to world No. 1, Trabert, in a high-quality four-set match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article0 |title=[No heading]. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=27 December 1954 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Rosewall also lost his singles match and the United States won back the cup after Seixas and Trabert defeated Hoad and Rosewall in four sets in the doubles rubber.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18443930 |title=U.S. wins back Davis Cup after lapse of 4 years. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=29 December 1954 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the end of an erratic and ultimately disappointing season Hoad's world ranking slipped to No. 7.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130986277 |title=Writer lists his 10 best: Hoad seventh. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=14 September 1954 |page=36 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130983653 |title=Hopman surveys tennis tour. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=27 September 1954 |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50609509 |title=Hoad was never in best form. |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |date=29 September 1954 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{efn|name=ranking|An alternative ranking compiled by an international team of tennis writers placed Hoad as No.5.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article69867758 |title=Trabert and Connolly head tennis ranking. |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)|The Advocate]] |location=Burnie, Tas. |date=30 November 1954 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>}} In a 1956 interview, Hoad admitted that especially in 1954 he often got fed-up with tennis and didn't care whether he played or not.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41851758 |title=The Hoads go on living in cases. |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | date=11 July 1956 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;1955\nHoad started the 1955 season on a low note when he was unable to play the South Australian tennis championship in early January due to a torn ligament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42851270 |title=Lewis Hoad not to play. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=31 December 1954 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> To some surprise he entered the mixed doubles event at the [[1955 Australian Championships]] with his girlfriend [[Jenny Staley]] and the pair finished as runner-ups to [[Thelma Coyne Long]] and [[George Worthington (tennis)|George Worthington]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71688321 |title=Lew and Jenny cause a stir. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=7 January 1955  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the singles event, Hoad reached his first Grand Slam tournament final after solid wins over Seixas (quarterfinal) and Hartwig (semifinal). In the final Rosewall's accuracy and control, however, were too strong for him and he lost in three straight sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75434956 |title=Rosewall Beats Hoad In Australian Tennis Final. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=3 February 1955 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad did not participate in the [[1955 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]] as the Davis Cup team that he was part of only left for Europe at the end of May during the Championships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91199733 |title=Davis Cup squad leaves for U.K. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=31 May 1955 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the singles final of the Queen's Club Championship in mid-June Hoad, who had gotten married earlier that day, lost his service seven times and lost to Rosewall in two straight sets but won the doubles event with Hartwig.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91201060 |title=Rosewall Wins Pre-Wimbledon Singles Title. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=20 June 1955 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71889118 |title=2-day honeymoon-then tennis. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=20 June 1955  |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was the fourth-seeded player at the [[1955 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]] at the end of June. In his quarterfinal match against seventh-seeded [[Budge Patty]], his game lacked accuracy and he conceded a break in each set resulting in a loss in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Budge Patty Upsets Hoad|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OfpXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=svYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6406%2C3529679|work=Spokane Daily Chronicle|date=27 June 1955}}</ref> Hoad was the second-seeded foreign player at the [[1955 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] in September held on the muddy courts of Forest Hills. In the quarterfinal, he lost his service three times in succession in the third set and suffered a straight-sets defeat in 50 minutes against Trabert, the first-seeded U.S. player, and eventual champion.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Hughes|editor1-first=G.P.|title=Dunlop Lawn Tennis Annual and Almanack 1956|date=1956|publisher=Dunlop Sports Co. Ltd.|location=London|page=185|oclc=877780619}}</ref> Having lost the Davis Cup in 1954, Australia had to play through the [[1955 Davis Cup]] preliminary rounds to challenge holders United States. In July, Australia defeated Mexico, Brazil and Canada to win the Americas Zone and subsequently beat Japan and Italy in the Inter-zone matches in August.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71674083 |title=U.S. morale slumps as Hoad hits form. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=17 August 1955 |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the Challenge Round, played at the West Side Tennis Club, Forest Hills from 26\u201328 August, Hoad defeated the French and Wimbledon champion Trabert in four sets in his first singles rubber and with Hartwig won the doubles match to reclaim the cup for Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91207884 |title=Second Singles Wins Sweep Australia To Five-nil Triumph. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=30 August 1955 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|author1=Alfred Wright|title=Lew Hoad's big serve carried the load|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=5 September 1955|volume=3|issue=10|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1955/09/05/666998/lew-hoads-big-serve-carried-the-load}}</ref> In his first significant tournament after the Davis Cup, Hoad won the New South Wales Championships in November after a win in the final against Rosewall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71781303 |title='Killer' Hoad fights for pro. offer. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=21 November 1955  |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71784888 |title=Rose must beat Lew for a career. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=8 December 1955  |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In December, he added the singles title at the Victorian Championships after a tough five-sets final win over 19-year old [[Ashley Cooper (tennis)|Ashley Cooper]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71785669 |title=Cooper heads for top of tennis. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]  |location=Melbourne |date=12 December 1955 |page=22 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the end of the year he was ranked No. 3 in the world according to Tingay.<ref name=collins/>\n\n;1956\n[[File:Hoad Rosewall Wimbledon.jpg|thumb|Hoad (left) and Rosewall playing doubles at the Wimbledon Championships in the mid-fifties]]\nHoad started the year with a five-set defeat in the final of the South Australian Championships against countryman [[Neale Fraser]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138116102 |title=Fraser Beats Hoad For S.A. Singles Title. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=3 January 1956 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the following Manly tournament, the crowd overflowed the stands during the final hindering Rosewall's baseline game more than Hoad's, resulting in a straight-sets win for Hoad in 35 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72529273 |title=Crowd hinders title tennis. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=9 January 1956  |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the [[1956 Australian Championships|Australian Championships]], played in Brisbane, Hoad overcame a two sets to one deficit against [[Mervyn Rose]] in the quarterfinal and beat Neale Fraser in the semifinal to reach his second consecutive Australian final. His opponent was again Ken Rosewall, and this time Hoad overcame his rival and titleholder in four sets to win his first Grand Slam singles title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138118099 |title=Australian title to Lew Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=31 January 1956 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72533139 |title=A few faces were red as.. Tired Lew takes first big title. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=31 January 1956  |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> His success was completed by winning the doubles title with Rosewall against Don Candy and Mervyn Rose. At the beginning of March, Hoad and his wife left for an overseas private tour, i.e. a tour sanctioned but not organized by the Australian tennis federation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79260823 |title=Hoads' tennis tour approved. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=23 February 1956 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75863577 |title=Australian ace on \"Pot-Hunting\" tour. |newspaper=[[The Mirror (Western Australia)|The Mirror]] |location=Perth |date=28 April 1956 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> First stop of the tour was Cairo where Hoad won the singles title at the Egyptian Championships against [[Sven Davidson]] followed by a tournament win in Alexandria over [[Fred Kovaleski]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79261724 |title=Egyptian Tennis Championships. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=15 March 1956 |page=29 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71794205 |title=Lew to play in final. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=26 March 1956 |page=17 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At Monte Carlo in late March, he was surprisingly beaten by Tony Vincent in the quarterfinal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79262527 |title=Vincent beats Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=5 April 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the Australian ranking published in April, reflecting the season until the end of March, Hoad overtook Rosewall as No. 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138122648 |title=Hoad Heads Rankings. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=17 April 1956 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Singles titles at the Lebanese Championships and at the Connaught Club in Essex followed in April but the month ended with a semifinal loss to [[Ham Richardson]] at the [[British Hard Court Championships]] in Bournemouth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71796881 |title=Hoad tokes two titles. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=11 April 1956  |page=26 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79263324 |title=Hoad In Three Title Wins. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=26 April 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75863630 |title=Lew Hoad beaten. |newspaper=[[The Mirror (Western Australia)|The Mirror]] |location=Perth |date=28 April 1956  |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nHoad won his first [[Italian Open (tennis)|Italian Championships]] on the clay courts of the [[Foro Italico]] in Rome in early May when he outplayed [[Sven Davidson]] in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aussie Lew Whips Sven|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=p8gxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HeMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4254%2C1928494|work=Ottawa Citizen|date=9 May 1956}}</ref> At the [[1956 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]], Hoad survived a five-set scare against [[Robert Abdesselam]] in the third round before winning the final against Sven Davidson in straight sets to claim his second consecutive Grad Slam singles title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71803802 |title=Hoad and Cooper win. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=19 May 1956  |page=33 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79264549 |title=Hoad takes French title. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=31 May 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Unknown to the public, Hoad had stayed up the night previous to the final, invited by a Russian diplomat, and was drunk when he came home. An intensive workout by [[Rod Laver]] got him into a state that allowed him to play the final.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=47|ps=}} In May, Hoad won the International Golden Ball tournament in [[Wiesbaden]], West Germany after a straight-sets victory in the final over [[Art Larsen]] but at the [[Barcelona Open (tennis)|Trofeo Conde de God\u00f3]] in Barcelona, he lost in the quarterfinal to [[Robert Howe (tennis)|Bob Howe]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hoad beats Larsen to win Wiesbaden tennis tourney|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/from-the-s-s-archives-hoad-beats-larsen-to-win-wiesbaden-tennis-tourney-1.78573|work=Stars and Stripes|date=15 May 1956}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El gran triunfo de Bob Howe sobre Lew Hoad ayer en el Trofeo Conde de Godo de Tenis|url=http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1956/05/25/pagina-28/32769566/pdf.html|work=La Vanguardia|date=2 June 1956|page=28}}</ref> As a preparation for Wimbledon, Hoad elected to play the singles event at the [[Northern Lawn Tennis Championships|Northern Championships]] in Manchester instead of the Queen's Club Championships. He reached the final but had to bow for 34-year old Jaroslav Drobn\u00fd who won the deciding set 7\u20135.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71808212 |title=Our Lew is beaten by Drobny. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=11 June 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91215723 |title=Rosewall favoured in Queen's tourney. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=19 June 1956 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was seeded first for the [[1956 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]] and was the pre-tournament favorite. He lost two sets along the way to reach the final, in which he faced Rosewall. In the first all-Australian final since 1922, Hoad was victorious in four sets to gain his first Wimbledon and third successive Grand Slam championship title.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hoad Wins Wimbledon Singles Tennis Crown|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nxkgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iGYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1688%2C644949|work=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=6 July 1956}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lew Hoad at Wimbledon crushes Rosewall for singles title|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ncgxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HuMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5125%2C679369|work=Ottawa Citizen|date=6 July 1956}}</ref> Hoad also won the doubles title with Rosewall, their third Wimbledon title, outclassing [[Orlando Sirola]] and [[Nicola Pietrangeli]] in the final in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79266105 |title=Wimbledon Tennis Hoad-Rosewall have grand doubles win. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=12 July 1956  |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Following his Wimbledon title he entered the Midlands tournament and was beaten in the semifinal by [[Mike Davies (tennis)|Mike Davies]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71646237 |title=He beat Lew \u2014but lost. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]  |location=Melbourne |date=16 July 1956 |page=24 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In August, Hoad won the singles title at the [[German Open Tennis Championships|German Championships]], held on the clay courts at [[Hamburg]], with a four-set defeat of [[Orlando Sirola]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79267163 |title=Mrs Long, Hoad Win Finals. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=9 August 1956  |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Wimbledon, Hoad experienced severe pain and stiffness in his lower back, at a level higher than before the tournament.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=113|ps=}} He arranged to travel to the U.S. by boat on the [[RMS Queen Mary]] rather than suffer a long plane trip.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=113|ps=}} However, the pain continued and reduced the level of his play for the remainder of the year and into 1957.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|pp=114\u2013116|ps=}}\n\nAfter his transatlantic voyage in August, Hoad played directly in the U.S. Championships, having missed the preparatory tournament at Newport.<ref>Sports Illustrated, 3 September 1956</ref> Having won the first three stages of the Grand Slam, Hoad was favoured to win the fourth and then turn professional for a lucrative contract offered by [[Jack Kramer]]. In an upset, however, he lost the final in four sets to Rosewall in the U.S. Championships at Forest Hills.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79268582 |title=Rosewall Great In Defeating Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=13 September 1956 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad and Rosewall won the doubles title against Seixas and Richardson.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91221586 |title=Hoad, Rosewall Win U.S Doubles Title. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=28 August 1956 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> After this, Hoad played in the O'Keefe Invitational at the Toronto Lawn Tennis Club in Rosedale, Toronto on a red clay surface. He defeated Luis Ayala in the semifinal and Sven Davidson in a four set final.<ref>New York Times, 14 September 1956, p.18</ref> At the [[Pacific Southwest Championships]] in September, the last leg of his overseas tour before returning to Australia, Hoad was beaten by [[Alex Olmedo]] in the third round.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79269227 |title=Hoad Defeated. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=27 September 1956 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91224212 |title=Hoad Back From Tour. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=29 September 1956 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In early November he lost the final of the Queensland Championships to Ashley Cooper in five sets and was hindered by numbness in the serving arm between the elbow and the wrist.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71763923 |title=\"Killer Coop\" beats Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=5 November 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The following week Hoad had to retire from the New South Wales Championships during his first round match against Ross Sherriff due to a sore arm.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71764827 |title=Hoad's arm is our big worry now. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=9 November 1956  |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In mid December Hoad and Rosewall competed in the final of the Victorian Championships which was their last final as amateurs as Rosewall turned professional at the end of the month. The final started late due to rain and was stopped due to darkness at two sets to one for Hoad but the following day Rosewall won the last two sets and the title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71771837 |title=The rains came to rob Rosewall. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=17 December 1956  |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71771913 |title=Tennis writer Ron asks: Why make enemies, Mr. Hoad?. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=18 December 1956 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In late December, Hoad was part of the Australian Davis Cup team which successfully defended the cup in the Challenge Round against the United States who were weakened by the absence of [[Tony Trabert]] who had turned professional in the fall of 1955. In his last Davis Cup appearance, Hoad won both his singles rubbers, against [[Herbie Flam]] and Seixas, as well as his doubles match with Rosewall to help Australia to a 5\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91230758 |title=Australia Wins Challenge Round 5-Love. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=29 December 1956 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad was confined to bed with back pain for the two days prior to the Davis Cup matches, and was relieved to find that he could play well.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=115|ps=}} At the end of the year, Hoad was ranked No. 1 in the world for the first time in his career.<ref name=collins/>\n\n;1957\nHoad played poorly in early 1957, due to back trouble, and was placed in an upper body cast for six weeks, following which he slowly returned to tennis competition in April 1957.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=115|ps=}} He then experienced a period of pain-free playing for 11 months. Hoad won his second successive Wimbledon singles title, defeating [[Ashley Cooper (tennis)|Ashley Cooper]] in a straight-sets final that lasted 57 minutes. After the tournament, he turned professional by signing a two-year contract with Kramer for a record guarantee of $125,000{{efn|name=prizemoney1959|Kramer claimed to have paid Hoad $140,000 through May 1958 and $225,000 through the end of June 1959.<ref name=\"pittstongazete195907102\">{{cite news |author=Harry Grayson |title=Why not Butch Buchholz? Everyone else tuns pro |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/79116185/ |work=Pittston Gazette |date=2 July 1959 |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>}} which included a $25,000 bonus for winning the 1957 Wimbledon singles title. In addition, Hoad would receive 20% of the gate receipts for each match, along with a 5% bonus if he won the match (against Gonzales).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48206279 |title=Jenny Hoad delayed Lew's tennis 'pro' career. |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | date=24 July 1957 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91592953 |title=Hoad Decides to Join Pro. Ranks. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=8 July 1957 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|p=229|ps=}} This \"percentage of gate\" clause of the contract would result in Hoad earning over \u00a350,000 sterling ($140,000) in the first 11 months of his pro career (through May, 1958) according to Kramer.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Jack Kramer Writes . . . I want Russia powerful in Tennis |magazine=British Lawn Tennis and Squash|date=August 1958 |volume=28 | number=303 |page=31}}</ref> Another report states \u00a371,400 sterling ($200,000) by late 1959.<ref name=\"ltab1960\">{{cite magazine |title=People and Places |magazine=Lawn Tennis and Badminton |date=15 January 1960 |volume=XLVI | issue=2 |page=23}}</ref> Hoad's biographers state that Hoad earned \"nearly $200,000\" by the end of the 1958 tour.<ref>Hodgson and Jones, P. 174</ref> By turning professional, Hoad was no longer eligible to compete in the amateur Grand Slam tournaments.\n\n===Professional career: 1957\u20131966===\nJack Kramer's first attempt to sign Hoad and Rosewall for his professional tour came in September 1954 when both players were in Los Angeles for the Pacific Coast Championships. Both signed a contract but later changed their minds and elected to remain amateurs.{{efn|name=contract|In his book ''The Game'' Kramer stated he did not publicly pursue this breach of contract, which would have made it impossible for Hoad and Rosewall to remain amateurs, because he felt it would ruin his position in Australia as well as the chance of signing both players at a later date.{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|p=226|ps=}}}}{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|pp=224\u2013226|ps=}}{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=24|ps=}} A renewed offer in October 1955 was also turned down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79256027 |title=Hoad decides not to turn professional. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=3 November 1955 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Fresh from his victory over Hoad at the 1956 U.S. Championships, it was Ken Rosewall who first signed the professional contract and went on to spend the new year as the regular victim of [[Pancho Gonzales]] on the pro tour.\n\n;1957\nIn July 1957, Hoad won his debut match as a professional against [[Frank Sedgman]] at the Forest Hills [[Tournament of Champions (tennis)|Tournament of Champions]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91593525 |title=Hoad Impressive In Professional Win. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=16 July 1957 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He won his next match, against [[Pancho Segura]], but then lost nine straight matches to various opponents as he adjusted to the pro tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad 1957 Player Activity|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=&sub=3&idjugador=48277&year=1957&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=&ronda=&tipoRanking=ATP&tm_category=&tm_torneo=&anno_from=&anno_to=&hand=&codpais=&rondaplus=&con_wj1wj2=&ranking_from=&ranking_to=#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> After Forest Hills, Hoad commented on the difference between amateur and professional tennis: ''\"It's an entirely different league. These pros make mistakes but they don't make them on vital points. That's the difference.\"''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91594180 |title=Gonzales Beats Hoad In Stirring Game. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=23 July 1957 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn September during a four-man tour of Europe by Hoad with Kramer, Rosewall, and Segura, Kramer and Hoad were interviewed by BBC television. Kramer stated in that interview his estimation of Hoad's game: \"I feel that he's potentially the best player that tennis might ever have.\"<ref>Getty Images, Collection:ITN, Clip #807918162, 9 September 1957</ref>\n\n;1958\nIn 1958 a series of 100 head-to-head matches was planned between Hoad and the reigning champion of professional tennis, Pancho Gonzales.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Neue Deutsche Wochenschau 418/1958|url=https://www.filmothek.bundesarchiv.de/video/586314|publisher=[[Bundesarchiv]]|date=31 January 1958|place=Melbourne, Australia| language=German}}</ref> The series started in January in a number of Australian cities in major stadiums on grass courts with a best-of-five set format, and at the end of the Australian subtour, Hoad was leading 8\u20135. The key match of the Australian series was the second Kooyong encounter, which Hoad won in four sets, a marathon 80 games, 4\u20136, 9\u20137, 11\u20139, 18\u201316 which leveled the series at five wins each.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=82|ps=}} Hoad followed-up with a 15 to 3 winning streak against Gonzales (including the non-tour Kooyong Tournament of Champions deciding match). In February, the series continued in the United States, mostly in indoor venues and local gyms with a best-of-three set format. Hoad won 18 of the first 27 matches, and on 28 February, Gonzales met with Kramer and indicated that he had lost confidence of winning the series. However, after they played an outdoor match on 1 March on a chilly night in [[Palm Springs]], Hoad's back stiffened which affected him significantly for the rest of the series. Twice Hoad was forced to take time off to rest his back and was substituted for in his absence by Rosewall and Trabert. From 9\u201318 Gonzales surged to a 26\u201323 lead, and at the end of the series on 8 June, he had defeated Hoad by 51 matches to 36.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91246825 |title=Gonzales Now Leads Hoad. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=2 April 1958 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Lew And Pancho Serve Up Tennis At Its Very Best|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=16 June 1958|volume=8|issue=24|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1002387/index.htm}}</ref>{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|pp=233\u2013235|ps=}} Gross receipts for the American portion of that series were reported in a Daily Mail interview with Hoad in 1959 to be $240,000.<ref name=\"dailymail19600104\">{{cite news |author=Jack Wood |title=Big Money Makes Hoad So Relaxed |work=[[Daily Mail]] |date=2 June 1959 |page=11}}</ref>\n\nFor the 1958/1959 seasons, Kramer had a powerful troupe of professional champions, including 11 Hall of Fame players, under contract, and he designed a series of major tournaments to provide a format in which all of them could participate. Kramer designated four tournaments as professional majors, Forest Hills, Kooyong, L.A. Masters, and Sydney White City.<ref>World Tennis, November, 1958</ref>{{page needed|date=January 2020}} Hoad won three of these eight tournaments in 1958/59.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=208\u20132016|ps=}} In January 1958, Hoad won the Kooyong Tournament of Champions in Melbourne, with prize money of AUS\u00a310,000 ($22,400). The tournament was funded by the Australian oil company [[Ampol]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91255316 |title=Draw for Ampol tennis fixed |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=15 January 1958 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hoad defeated Gonzales in the deciding match, and won all five of his matches in the round-robin event. He received AUS\u00a32,500 ($5,600) for his win, $6,160 including doubles returns, a record payday in pro tennis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91256420 |title=Hoad fancied for Ampol Round Robin |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=29 January 1958 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In the final of the Cleveland World Pro on 5 May, Hoad lost a two-set lead against Gonzales while struggling with a leg-muscle injury.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=83|ps=}} Hoad dropped out of the tour in late May to rest his thigh injury.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=83|ps=}} At the Forest Hills Tournament of Champions in June 1958, Hoad's thigh injury healed in time for his final match which he won against Gonzales on the final day in a weekend match televised nationally on [[CBS]].{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=209|ps=}} The reporter for the L.A. Times called this Hoad/Gonzales broadcast \"one of the most sensational displays of tennis that I can remember.\"<ref>L.A. Times, 5 July 1958</ref> However, Gonzales won the event with a better overall round-robin record. At Roland Garros in September, Hoad won his quarterfinal against Trabert, and his semifinal against Gonzales.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=211|ps=}} While leading in the final against Rosewall, Hoad wrenched his back reaching for a ball, and could not play well in the remainder of the match.<ref>The Times of London, 20\u201322 September 1958</ref> He had to default the [[Wembley Championships|Wembley Pro tournament]] in September due to an \"arthritic\" back.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Around the World...|journal=World Tennis|date=November 1958|volume=6|issue=6|page=50}}</ref> Hoad rested for the next three months and did not play again until 1959. Hoad had earned nearly $200,000 by the end of the 1958 season.\n\n;1959\nIn early 1959, he began Kramer's Ampol Open Trophy world series of tournaments slowly, hampered by an elbow injury.<ref>Chicago Tribune, 1 March  1959, p.258</ref> However, at the end of January, Hoad defeated Rosewall and Cooper to win at Perth and in February 1959, he defeated Rosewall in three sets to win the South Australian Pro Championships in Adelaide. This gave Hoad the lead in Ampol bonus points after the first group of five tournaments, a lead which he would never relinquish until the Ampol Open Trophy series ended in January 1960.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=212|ps=}} The Ampol Open Trophy series resumed in North America in June with the L.A. Masters at the L.A. Tennis Club on cement, followed by the O'Keefe Professional Championships at the [[Toronto Lawn Tennis Club]] in [[Rosedale, Toronto|Rosedale]] on red clay,{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=93|ps=}} and the Forest Hills Tournament of Champions in New York City at the Forest Hills stadium on grass. \n\nIn the four-man 1959 Kramer World Professional Championship Tour, which ran from 20 February through May in the United States, Hoad built a lead of 12 to 5 in his series of matches against Gonzales, after a win in Newcastle, Pennsylvania in late April.<ref>L'Impartial, Saturday, 25 April. 1959. P.7</ref> Gonzales stated that \"I had blisters under my blisters from the punishment\" on that tour.<ref>N.Y. Times, 23 Jan. 1970. P. 56</ref>  However, the daily grind of the tour began to cause a renewal of Hoad's back trouble,<ref>Hodgson and Jones, P. 175</ref> and he finally won against Gonzales by 15 matches to 13. He also won his head-to-head's with newly turned pro [[Ashley Cooper (tennis)|Ashley Cooper]] (18\u20132) and Mal Anderson (9\u20135). With a win-loss record of 42\u201320 he finished second in the four-man tour ranking behind Gonzales (47\u201315) and earned $28,250.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Around the World...|magazine=World Tennis|date=July 1959|volume=7|issue=2|pages=61, 67}}</ref>{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=92, 212|ps=}} Gross receipts for that 100-day  American series were reported in a Daily Mail interview with Hoad as $160,000.<ref name=\"dailymail19600104\">{{cite news |author=Jack Wood |title=Big Money Makes Hoad So Relaxed |work=[[Daily Mail]] |date=2 June 1959 |page=11}}</ref>\n\nAt the Cleveland World Pro Championships in late April, not part of the Ampol Open Trophy series, Hoad lost the final to Gonzales in three straight sets.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=92, 212|ps=}}\n\nAt the L.A. Masters round robin tournament from 5 to 14 June, part of the Ampol series, Hoad and Gonzales both finished with five wins and one loss, but Gonzales won the title on account of his victory over Hoad in their head-to-head match.<ref name=\"lat19600615\">{{cite news |author=Jamie Curran |title=Gonzales wins pro masters net tourney |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/380677970/ |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=15 June 1960 |page=1 Part IV|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the tournament, Hoad received several Hollywood offers for screen tests, but turned them down with the comment \"What do I want with money?\".{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=92|ps=}}\n\nAt the Forest Hills Tournament of Champions in June 1959, part of the Ampol series, and broadcast nationally on the CBS television network, Hoad defeated Rosewall in the semifinal and Gonzales in the final, both in four sets, to claim the title.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=212|ps=}} According to tennis journalist and author Joe McCauley this was the [[zenith]] of Hoad's career.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=93|ps=}} In the August 1959 issue of World Tennis, Riggs wrote of the Forest Hills final, \"the match signified the end of an era. The great Gonzales who had dominated professional tennis for four years had been decisively beaten...\"<ref name=\"World Tennis, August, 1959\">World Tennis, August, 1959</ref>{{page needed|date=January 2020}} In that same issue of World Tennis, it was noted that Hoad had been seeded No. 1 at Forest Hills and Gonzales seeded No. 2 on the basis of Ampol points.<ref name=\"World Tennis, August, 1959\"/> In August 1959, Hoad finished runner-up to Cooper at the Slazenger Professional Tournament in Eastbourne, not part of the Ampol series.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Tournament results \u2013 England|journal=World Tennis|date=October 1959|volume=7|issue=5|page=78}}</ref> In September, Hoad lost to Sedgman in the semifinal of the French Pro at Roland Garros but defeated Rosewall in a playoff for third place. In the Grand Prix de Europe regional tour of European locations from August to October, which excluded Roland Garros and Wembley (components of the Ampol series), Hoad finished in third place behind Sedgman and Rosewall (Gonzales defaulted the European tour), and at the end of 1959, Kramer placed Hoad in fourth place in his personal world professional rating, while the French sportspaper [[L'\u00c9quipe]] ranked Hoad fifth as of mid-December, before the Ampol series was completed.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=97|ps=}}<ref>L'Equipe, 17 December, 1959.</ref> However, Kramer's Australian tennis agent Bob Barnes placed Hoad in first spot, corresponding to Hoad's standing on the official Ampol ranking.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Around the World...|journal=World Tennis|date=December 1959|volume=7|issue=7|page=44}}</ref> \n\nThe Ampol Open Trophy series moved back from Europe to Australia where it was completed with five tournaments in November and December/January. Hoad won the Perth and Adelaide events to begin the final group of tournaments.<ref name= \"argus1959\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131614593 |title=World Tennis Championship |newspaper=[[The Cumberland Argus]] |date=23 September 1959 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At the Sydney Tournament of Champions from 8 to 13 December, Gonzales defeated Rosewall in the semifinal and Hoad in the final, both in straight sets.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=215|ps=}} At Brisbane from December 15 to 19, Rosewall defeated Hoad in the semifinal and Gonzales in the final in long matches.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=215|ps=}} The final event of the Ampol Open Trophy world series, the Qantas Kooyong Championships, began on 26 December 1959 with prize money of AUS\u00a36,000 ($13,440).<ref name=\"theage19600104\">{{cite news |author1=Don Lawrence |title=Tennis final to Lew Hoad |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/120978356 |work=[[The Age]] |date=4 January 1960 |page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> With a victory at Kooyong, either Hoad or Gonzales would have won the Ampol Open Trophy series, but Gonzales decided to return to the U.S. for the holidays to be with his fianc\u00e9e.<ref>L'Impartial, 6 January, 1960, P.9</ref> Gonzales, in withdrawing from the Qantas Kooyong, thereby defaulted the Ampol series and Open Trophy to Hoad.\n\nOn 2 January 1960, Hoad defeated Rosewall in a three-hour, four-set match to win the Qantas Kooyong round-robin tournament,{{efn|name=kooyong1960|Hoad and Rosewall both had a 4\u20131 win/loss record but Hoad finished first due to his win over Rosewall.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=216|ps=}} }} a match which Kramer acclaimed as one of the best ever played.<ref name=\"theage19600104\"/> With this win also came the Ampol Open Trophy win,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131618684/15033875 |title=Search for world's best tennis star |newspaper=[[The Cumberland Argus]] | location=New South Wales, Australia |date=14 January 1959 |page=9 |via=Trove }}</ref> and a bonus prize of AUS\u00a32,500 ($5,600) for winning the Ampol Open Trophy.<ref name= \"argus1959\"/> The Ampol Open Trophy world series had consisted of 15 tournaments around the world played between 10 January 1959 and 2 January 1960.{{efn|name=kramertour|According to the Kramer Tour brochure for 1959, the 15 tournaments were Melbourne (10 Jan), Brisbane (20 Jan), Perth (26 Jan), Sydney (4 Feb), Adelaide (11 Feb), L.A. Masters (5 Jun), Toronto (16 Jun), Forest Hills (23 Jun), Roland Garros (8 Sep), Wembley (19 Sep), Perth (26 Nov), Adelaide (1 Dec), White City (8 Dec), Brisbane (15 Dec), Kooyong (25 Dec).}} Hoad finished first in the series with 51 bonus points, ahead of Gonzales (43 points) and Rosewall (41 points), Sedgman (35 points), Trabert (28 points).{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=97, 99|ps=}}<ref name=\"theage19600104\"/><ref>Kramer Tour 1959 brochure</ref> Hoad won six of the 15 tournaments and 71% (36/51) of his matches in the series,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: 1959 Player Activity|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=3&idjugador=48277&year=1959&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=&ronda=&tipoRanking=ATP&tm_category=&tm_torneo=&anno_from=&anno_to=&hand=&codpais=&rondaplus=&con_wj1wj2=&ranking_from=&ranking_to=#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: 1960 Player Activity|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=3&idjugador=48277&year=1960&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=&ronda=&tipoRanking=ATP&tm_category=&tm_torneo=&anno_from=&anno_to=&hand=&codpais=&rondaplus=&con_wj1wj2=&ranking_from=&ranking_to=#aSubmenu|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> while Gonzales won four tournaments and 72% (26/36) of his matches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pancho Gonzales: 1959 Player Activity|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player1=GONZALES,%20PANCHO&sub=3&idjugador=46369&year=1959&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=&ronda=&tipoRanking=ATP&tm_category=&tm_torneo=&anno_from=&anno_to=&hand=&codpais=&rondaplus=&con_wj1wj2=&ranking_from=&ranking_to=#aSubmenu|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> Gonzales defaulted three Ampol tournaments, and played 15 fewer matches than Hoad. Hoad was three wins and five losses in matches against Gonzales in the Ampol world series, although Hoad and Gonzales were two wins and two losses against each other in tournament deciding matches. Hoad won six of his eight matches against Rosewall on the Ampol world series.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=211\u2013216|ps=}} The Melbourne newspaper \"The Age\" for 4 January 1960 declared, Hoad \"was crowned the new world professional tournament champion at Kooyong\" by winning the Ampol world series.<ref name=\"theage19600104\"/> French language \"L'Impartial\" for 6 January 1960 declared \"Lewis Hoad world champion\", the win at Kooyong \"allows him at the same time to claim the world title for 1959\".<ref name=\"impartial1960\">{{cite news |title=Tennis \u2013 Lewis Hoad champion du monde |url=http://www.limpartialarchives.ch/Olive/APA/SwissSNP_Fr/sharedpages/SharedView.Page.aspx?sk=BFEE6E15&href=IMP%2F1960%2F01%2F06&page=9 |work=[[L'Impartial]] |date=6 January 1960 |page=9 |language=French}}</ref> The order of finish of the 12 professionals on the Ampol world series was designated by Kramer to be the official ranking for 1959, and determined the seeding list for all tournaments.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=97|ps=}}.<ref name= \"argus1959\"/> The field of professional players for the Ampol series included 11 present-day members of the International Tennis Hall of Fame.{{efn|name=ampol|The 11 members of the International Tennis Hall of Fame on the 1959/60 Ampol world tour, all of whom won major singles titles, were Hoad, Gonzales, Rosewall, Sedgman, Trabert, Segura, Anderson, Cooper, Rose, McGregor, Olmedo.}} This would turn out to be Hoad's only professional world championship world series victory in three full attempts, and the only world championship tournament series reported between 1946 and 1964.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=97, 192, 235|ps=}}\n\nKramer's office reported that for the 1959 year as a whole, Hoad had won his personal series of matches against Gonzales 24 to 23.<ref name=\"theage19600104\"/><ref name=\"sh19600110\"/> He withdrew from the 1960 world championship tour, citing a need for family time.<ref name=\"theage19591224\">{{cite news |author1=Don Lawrence |title=Lew Hoad withdraws from 1960 tennis tour |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/122238586/ |work=[[The Age]] |date=24 December 1959 |page=16|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nBy then Hoad had made, according to one report, approximately $200,000 since turning pro,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Around the World...|journal=World Tennis|date=February 1960|volume=7|issue=9|page=44}}</ref> while another report had his career earnings at $224,000 including $70,000 in 1959 alone.<ref name=\"sh19600110\">{{cite news |author1=David Burke |title=Hoad takes stock |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/122787666/ |work=[[The Sun-Herald]] |date=10 January 1960 |page=33|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hoad's biographers stated that he made \"almost $200,000\" by the end of the 1958 season. Kramer stated that he paid Hoad $140,000 through May, 1958 and $225,000 through June of 1959, not including promotional money, with much of the 1959/60 season still to come.<ref>Pittston Gazette, 2 July, 1959.</ref> The total before promotions would be well over $250,000 through 1959, at least twice the level of his contract guarantee of $125,000. Hoad also estimated his endorsement income at about $22,400 per year, plus investment returns on a hotel ownership with other players.<ref name=\"sh19600110\"/> It was reported that Hoad would likely earn more in 1959 than top baseball player [[Mickey Mantle]]{{efn|name=sabr|In 1958, Mantle was the highest paid baseball player earning $65,000, and in 1959 [[Willie Mays]] was the highest paid baseball player earning $75,000.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Michael Haupert |title=MLB's annual salary leaders since 1874 |url=https://sabr.org/research/mlbs-annual-salary-leaders-1874-2012 |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research}}</ref>}} and the best-paid American football players.<ref name=\"chicagotribune19590301\">{{cite news |title=Jack Kramer \u2013 golden boy of tennis |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/372472835 |work=[[The Chicago Tribune]] |author=David Condon |date=1 March 1959 |page=30|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> \n\n;1960\nHoad had been the number-one money winner in pro tennis for both 1958 and 1959, and his initial contract with Kramer was renegotiated in early February 1960, as well as Rosewall's, for a seven year term to run through the 1966 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Writers predict 'cold' future for Wimbledon |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=VJOaslTFpLQC&dat=19600208&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |work=[[St. Joseph Gazette]] |date=8 February 1960 |page=7 |quote=Kramer did more than talk yesterday. He signed up Ken Rosewall and Lew Hoad for another seven years.}}</ref> Hoad took a three-month layoff at the beginning of 1960 to rest his back and spend time with his family.<ref name=\"sh19600110\"/><ref name=\"ltab1960\"/> When he returned to play, he was rusty, slow, and carried some extra weight, but he gradually recovered his form. He won a New Zealand tour in April, over Anderson, Sedgman, and Cooper.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=216|ps=}} In May, he lost a five-set final to Rosewall at the Melbourne Olympic Pool where a court was set up on the drained pool floor.<ref>{{cite news | title=Rosewall pro tennis champ | work=Los Angeles Times | date=11 May 1960 | pages=4}}</ref> Hoad won tournament finals in June at Santa Barbara, California and in September at Geneva, Switzerland, both over Rosewall, but appeared out of condition in the Roland Garros final against Rosewall.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=217|ps=}} In late 1960, Hoad won the first Japanese Professional Championships in Tokyo, beating Rosewall, Cooper, and Gimeno to win the $10,000 tournament.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=103, 218|ps=}} In the final, Hoad prevailed at 13\u201311 in the fifth set over Rosewall.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=103, 218|ps=}}\n\n;1961\n[[File:Lew Hoad and Robert Haillet at Professional Championship Noordwijk 1961.jpg|thumb|Lew Hoad and [[Robert Haillet]] (right) at the Professional Championship in [[Noordwijk]], Netherlands in August 1961.]]\nHoad played a few matches on the 1961 pro championship tour in January, but soon withdrew because of a broken left foot and was substituted for by first Trabert and then Sedgman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103117073 |title=Hoad breaks left foot |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=23 March 1961 |page=31 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103117207 |title=Hoad planning month's rest |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=24 March 1961  |page=31 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He finished fourth in a tour of five Soviet cities in July.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=220\u2013221|ps=}} In September, Hoad lost in the first round of the French Pro to [[Luis Ayala]],{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=221|ps=}} and at the Wembley Pro, he defeated Gonzales in a four-set semifinal but lost in a four-set final to Rosewall, appearing stiff and sluggish.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=112, 222|ps=}} Also that month, Hoad and Gonzales had already played a ten-match tour of Britain and Ireland, with Buchholz and Davies playing the undercard matches.<ref name=\"sh19611008\">{{cite news |author1=Eddie Oakes |title=Pros. plan busy Aust. tour |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121276234 |work=[[The Sun-Herald]] |date=8 October 1961 |page=62|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hoad won his series against Gonzales by a score of six matches to four.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Vera McWeeny |title=Vera McWeeney on Tennis |work=[[Irish Independent]] |date=16 September 1961 |page=18|via=Irish Newspaper Archives}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lew Hoad Wins at St Annes |work=[[Lytham Evening Gazette]] |date=11 September 1961 }}</ref> (The Sun-Herald, 8 October 1961, relying on the \"Australian pros\", reported Hoad winning seven of ten matches on that tour.<ref name=\"sh19611008\"/>) Hoad won four of the five matches in the series which were played on grass.<ref>Hoad won on grass at Bristol, Leeds, Scarborough, and St. Annes, Gonzales won on grass at Dublin. / Scarborough News, 2 September 1961 / Yorkshire Evening Post, 3 September 1961 / St. Annes News 10 September 1961 / Irish Examiner, 27 August 1961</ref><ref name=\"gsta\">{{cite web|title=1961 British tour matches|url=http://www.tennis.co.nf/1961ukireland.htm|website=www.tennis.co.nf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=British Pro Tour|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=tournament&accion=draw&torneoSearchEnc=BRITISH%20PRO%20TOUR&year=1961|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> The four players shared AUS\u00a39,000 ($20,160).<ref name=\"sh19611008\"/> In November, Hoad won the fifth and deciding rubber for Australia against the United States in the inaugural Kramer Cup (the pro equivalent of the Davis Cup) by beating Trabert in four sets. Trabert said afterwards: \"Trying to stop Lew in that final set was like fighting a machine gun with a rubber knife\".{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=115|ps=}} [[L'\u00c9quipe]] ranked Hoad as the third-best player of the year.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=116|ps=}} In July 1961 Gardnar Mulloy rated Hoad as world No. 1 ahead of Gonzales, and the favourite to win a prospective open Wimbledon.<ref name=\"miaminews19610716\">{{cite news |author=John Crittenden |title=Barriers to crumble at Wimbledon -- Gar |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/302057845/ |work=[[Miami News]] |date=16 July 1961 |page=4C |via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n;1962\nThere was no official pro championship tour in 1962, as Laver had declined to accept pro offers made by Kramer at the 1961 Wimbledon. Kramer resigned as tour promoter and director. Kramer's continuing player contracts, Hoad's contract among them, were assumed by the players in their own association, the International Professional Tennis Players Association.<ref name=\"wtjuly1963\">{{cite magazine|title=The Wild World of the Pros|magazine=World Tennis|date=July 1963|volume=11}}</ref>{{page needed|date=January 2020}} From 14 to 17 March 1962, Hoad won the Adelaide Professional Championships, beating Rosewall, Gimeno, and Sedgman, the final against Rosewall very close. On 12 August 1962, Hoad was awarded the Facis Trophy for winning the Italian tour.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=224|ps=}} In late August, Hoad played a five-match, best-of-three sets tour in Britain against Trabert, defeating Trabert at Nottingham, Edinburgh, Bournemouth, and Dublin, while Trabert won at Scarborough.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=225|ps=}} Hoad won the professional tournament in [[Z\u00fcrich]] in September 1962 by a win in the final against Pancho Segura.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131779146 |title=Hoad new champion. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=11 September 1962 |page=28 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref> In late September, Hoad lost to Rosewall in a 3 1/4 hour, four-set final at Wembley.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=119, 230|ps=}} Hoad and Rosewall teamed to win the doubles final at both Roland Garros and Wembley. In the 1962 Kramer Cup tournament, in best-of-five set formats, Hoad defeated Gimeno in the semifinal tie in Turin, Italy on clay, and Hoad won the opening match of the final at Adelaide in December against Olmedo on grass.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=226\u2013227|ps=}} Hoad was voted the top tennis player of 1962 in a poll by 85 U.S. sports editors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article104257599 |title=Lew Hoad Mr. Tennis. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=30 January 1963 |page=30 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;1963\nIn January 1963, Hoad and Rosewall guaranteed the contract of new pro Rod Laver, and Hoad and Rosewall, longtime teammates, became the proprietors of the professional tour.{{efn|name=1963tour|Trabert remained for some months as tour director before pursuing other interests.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=125|ps=}} Kramer would continue as occasional advisor, and helped to arrange the 1963 Forest Hills U.S. Pro tournament.}}<ref>{{cite web |author1=Richard Williams |title=Age of the rocket man |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/age-of-the-rocket-man-wimbledon-has-seen-many-great-players-but-none-more-so-than-rod-laver-the-5ft-1492771.html |website=[[The Independent]] |date=20 June 1993}}</ref>{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=121|ps=}} Hoad agreed to reduce his own share of money taken in at the gate for the upcoming 1963 tour of Australia (his share dropped to 15%) in order for Laver to be able to take 25% of the gate, which arrangement would help Laver earn his guarantee more quickly.<ref>{{cite news |title=Laver Rapped for Cup Play |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/pacific-stars-and-stripes-dec-25-1962-p-13 |work=[[Pacific Stars and Stripes]] |date=25 December 1962 |page=13|via=[[Newspaperarchive.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In January, Hoad went 8\u20130 over Laver in a series of matches in Australia, some of which were best-of-five and televised from sold-out stadiums.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=227|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad vs Rod Laver Head 2 Head|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> (Laver and Buchholz, who was also present on the undercard of the tour, both later claimed that there were 13 matches and a 13 to zero score for Hoad over Laver.<ref name=\"bodo2007\">{{cite web |author1=Peter Bodo |title=TMF: best of 5, all the time! |url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2007/04/tmf-best-of-5-all-the-time/44510/ |website=[[Tennis.com]] |date=4 April 2007}}</ref><ref>Richard Evans, TennisHalloFame, January 22, 2019  https://twitter.com/TennisHalloFame</ref>) Hoad was then inactive for five months due to a shoulder injury.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=228|ps=}} On his return in June, he lost to Laver in the semifinal of the Adler Pro, and at the Forest Hills U.S. Pro tournament he lost to Buchholz in the first round. The Forest Hills event did not have a television contract, was a financial failure, and the players, with the exception of Gonzales, were not paid.<ref name=collins/><ref>{{cite news |author1=Dave Anderson |title=The grandeur that was Hoad |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/09/11/archives/the-grandeur-that-was-hoad.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=11 September 1977 |page=181}}</ref> At the French Pro indoor event at [[Stade Pierre de Coubertin (Paris)|Stade Coubertin]] in September, Hoad was defeated in straight sets by Rosewall in the semifinal and lost the third place play-off against Sedgman. At the Wembley Pro, he reached the final after surviving a marathon semifinal against Buchholz in which he strained his leg muscle and was limping throughout most of the match. Hoad was tired and sluggish in the final,{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=125|ps=}} which again he lost to Rosewall, this time in four sets.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=230|ps=}} McCauley acclaimed the semi-final with Buchholz \"one of the best contests ever staged at Wembley\".{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=125|ps=}} At the end of the year, Laver had become the No. 2 professional player behind Rosewall,{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=228|ps=}} although Hoad held a head-to-head advantage over Laver on the year.\n\nHoad's gross earnings from tennis play for the year were about $20,000, or fifth among the pro players.<ref>{{cite news |title=Laver's $60,000 Tops Pro Tennis Earnings |work=[[New York Herald Tribune]] |date=9 January 1964 |page=9}}</ref> However, in addition to this prize money, Hoad's contract and the guarantees associated with it were reportedly met by a distribution of tournament profits above the purse prize money to meet his contract rights, inherited from the Kramer era by the IPTPA.<ref name=\"wtjuly1963\"/>{{page needed|date=January 2020}}. Gonzales expressed disapproval of the distribution of profits to those players with guaranteed contract levels. \n\n;1964\u201366  \nIn February and March 1964, Hoad played a 16-day 24-match best-of-three sets tour of New Zealand with Laver, Rosewall, and Anderson. Hoad and Laver both finished on top with seven wins and five losses, but Hoad won first place with a 3 to 1 head-to-head score against Laver.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=231|ps=}} <ref>New Zealand Herald, 29 February, March 1964 / Christchurch Star, 16 March 1964</ref> In late September 1964, Hoad and Gonzales played a four match best-of-three sets head-to-head series in Britain, at Brighton, Carlyon Bay (Cornwall), Cardiff (Wales), and Glasgow (Scotland). Hoad won the first three matches at Brighton, Carlyon Bay, and Cardiff, while Gonzales won the final match at Glasgow.<ref>TennisBase, Hoad/Gonzales matches, 1964</ref> Hoad experienced foot trouble in 1964 and finished in sixth place in the tournament series points system.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=235|ps=}} In early 1965, much of his large right toe was removed, and he was only able to play a limited schedule thereafter.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=132|ps=}} Hoad won his final victory against Laver on 24 January 1966 at White City in Sydney, his home town, defeating him in straight sets.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=240|ps=}} Back problems plagued Hoad throughout his career and forced his retirement from the tennis tour in 1967 but the advent of the [[Open Era]] enticed him to make sporadic comebacks.<ref name=theage19670609>{{cite news|title=Hoad may retire to coaching|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WdRYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Y5MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4151%2C1413273|work=The Age|date=9 June 1967}}</ref>\n\nAccording to research done for a 1970 British Path\u00e9 documentary film on Hoad's tennis ranch, Hoad had earned GBP 350,000 ($840,000 in 1970 exchange rates) during the course of his playing career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Australian Former Champion Lew Hoad Establishes Tennis School In Spain. |url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA59IBG5MPTC1GB4ZLDYAK4EOXE-SPAIN-AUSTRALIAN-FORMER-CHAMPION-LEW-HOAD-ESTABLISHES-TENNIS |work=[[British Path\u00e9]] |date=20 February 1970 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Computing 'Real Value' Over Time with a Conversion between U.K. Pounds and U.S. Dollars, 1791 to Present |url=https://www.measuringworth.com/calculators/exchange/ |website=MeasuringWorth}}</ref> \n\nIn a 1977 newspaper interview, Hoad's career earnings were stated to be GBP 250,000<ref>{{cite news |author=Jack Monet |title=Nowadays, Lew Hoad Is Helpful on the Tennis Court |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] (European Edition) |date=30 April 1977 |page=13}}</ref> ($436,000 per 1977 exchange rate).<ref>{{cite web |title=Computing 'Real Value' Over Time with a Conversion between U.K. Pounds and U.S. Dollars, 1791 to Present |url=https://www.measuringworth.com/calculators/exchange/ |website=MeasuringWorth}}</ref>\n\n===Open era===\nHoad participated in the 1967 [[Wimbledon Pro]], a three-day BBC televised tournament organized by the [[All-England Club]] as a trial for \"open\" tennis and as such the first Wimbledon tournament open to male professional tennis players. Hoad was one of the eight players invited for the singles event and despite being in semi-retirement and without competitive play for ten months,{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=244\u2013248|ps=}} he won his first match against 39-year-old Gonzales in three sets.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=UK: Wimbledon World Professional Tennis Championship 1967|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVAAKU6R1B7HWL6VCU8HNWU7TK4Y-UK-WIMBLEDON-WORLD-PROFESSIONAL-TENNIS-CHAMPIONSHIP|publisher=[[British Path\u00e9]]|date=25 August 1967|place=London}}</ref> The BBC television commentator called it \"the finest match ever seen on these hallowed grounds.\"{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=139|ps=}} This would be the last match on grass between Hoad and Gonzales, with Hoad holding a lifetime edge on grass over Gonzales of 20 matches to 14.<ref>TennisBase, lifetime hth statistics</ref><ref>local British newspapers 1961 tour / Irish Examiner, August 27, 1961 / Yorkshire Evening Post, September 3, 1961 / St. Annes News, September 10, 1961 / Hoad won on grass at Bristol,Leeds, Scarborough, St. Annes, Gonzales won on grass at Dublin</ref> With little energy left he lost the semifinal to Rosewall in two straight sets.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|pp=142\u2013145|ps=}} Hoad reached the final of the [[Irish Open (tennis)|Irish Championships]] at Dublin in July 1968 but lost to [[Tom Okker]] in straight sets, hampered by a thigh injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article107062703 |title=Laver scores again. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=15 July 1968 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In November 1969, Hoad won the [[Dewar Cup Aberavon]] singles title, part of the Dewar Cup indoor circuit, after defeating [[Bob Hewitt]] in the final in two sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hoad shines in Dewar Cup|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vBEQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rZADAAAAIBAJ&pg=3510%2C714046|work=The Age|date=3 November 1969}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hoad threat again|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vhEQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rZADAAAAIBAJ&pg=3965%2C987092|work=The Age|date=5 November 1969}}</ref> At the [[1970 Italian Open (tennis)|1970 Italian Open]], he reached the third round which he lost in four sets to [[Alex Metreveli]]. At the [[1970 French Open]], he defeated Pasarell in four close sets, and reached the fourth round before succumbing to eventual finalist [[\u017deljko Franulovi\u0107]]. At Wimbledon that year he lost in the second round to [[Ismail El Shafei]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Fred Tupper |title=Wimbledon cheers Hoad, 35, as he loses 5\u2010set struggle against El Shafei |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/25/archives/wimbledon-cheers-hoad-35-as-he-loses-5set-struggle-against-el.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 June 1970}}</ref> In the spring of 1972, Hoad teamed up with [[Frew McMillan]] to play the doubles event at the [[1972 Italian Open (tennis)|Italian Open]] and reached the final against [[Ilie N\u0103stase]] and [[Ion \u0162iriac]]. They led 2\u20130 in sets but retired at 3\u20135 down in the fifth set in protest of the poor light conditions and the antics of the Rumanian pair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hoad stalks off court|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YsgQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tJADAAAAIBAJ&pg=4809%2C764737|work=The Age|date=4 May 1972}}</ref><ref name=wot73>{{cite book|title=World of Tennis '73 : a BP and Commercial Union yearbook|year=1973|publisher=Queen Anne Press|location=London|isbn=9780671216238|pages=117\u2013119|editor=[[John Barrett (tennis)|John Barrett]]}}</ref> At the end of June, at the age of 37, he made his final [[1972 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] appearance losing in the first round to [[J\u00fcrgen Fassbender]] in four sets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article102028560 |title=Veterans bow to youth at Wimbledon. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=28 June 1972 |page=34 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1970 to 1974, Hoad was the coach of the Spanish Davis Cup team.<ref name=ww1974/>\n\n==Playing style==\n\nStrength of arm and wrist played an important part in Hoad's game, as he often drove for winners rather than rallying and waiting for the right opportunity. Although he assaulted his opponents, he also had the skill to win the [[French Open|French Championships]] on the slower clay court. Hoad played right-handed and had a powerful serve and groundstrokes but his game lacked consistency.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article58103747 |title=How Vic Seixas rates our men. |newspaper=[[The Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail]] |location=Adelaide |date=21 August 1954  |page=44 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130984229 |title=Hoad \"too erratic to be great\". |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=2 September 1954 |page=48 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71647677 |title=It's Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hoad! |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]]  |date=23 July 1956  |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> At times Hoad had difficulty maintaining concentration.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=10|ps=}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18447077 |title=Hoad's main problem now himself. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=1 December 1954 |page=17 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71805343 |title=Lew's biggest rival is Hoad |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |date=26 May 1956 |page=5 (The Argus Weekender) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> According to Kramer, \"Hoad had the loosest game of any good kid I ever saw. There was absolutely no pattern to his game.... He was the only player I ever saw who could stand six or seven feet behind the baseline and snap the ball back hard, crosscourt. He'd try for winners off everything, off great serves, off tricky short balls, off low volleys. He hit hard overspin drives, and there was no way you could ever get him to temporise on important points.\"<ref name=sahof>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame \u2013 Lew Hoad \u2013 Tennis|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=390&memberType=athlete|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame}}</ref> Kramer compares Hoad to [[Ellsworth Vines]].  \"''Both were very strong guys. Both succeeded at a very young age.... Also, both were very lazy guys. Vines lost interest in tennis (for golf) before he was thirty, and Hoad never appeared to be very interested. Despite their great natural ability, neither put up the outstanding records that they were capable of. Unfortunately, the latter was largely true because both had physical problems.''\"{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|pp=229,230|ps=}} \n\nHoad was runner-up for the Australian junior table tennis championship in 1951, and developed strong wrists and arms through heavy weight-lifting regimes.  Hoad would use wrist strength in his strokes to make last split-second changes in racquet direction. He would saw off about a half inch from the ends of his racquet handles, which were short to begin with, and move the grip higher to wield his racquets as if they were ping-pong bats.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=234|ps=}}\n\n==Assessment==\nIn 1956, his win/loss ratio in all matches was 114/129 or 88%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: 1956 Player Activity|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=&sub=3&idjugador=48277&year=1956&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=&ronda=&tipoRanking=ATP&tm_category=&tm_torneo=&anno_from=&anno_to=&hand=&codpais=&rondaplus=&con_wj1wj2=&ranking_from=&ranking_to=#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> His win ratio in an injury-plagued 1958 was 41% (winning 64 of 155 matches).<ref>{{cite web|title=1958 Ranking Singles|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=rankings&accion=single&lista=1701&apartado=tm&fecha=29-12-1958|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> Hoad's win rates on the world championship tour that year (36/87 or 41%) and in the 1959 four-man tour (68%) compare favourably to Rosewall's percentages on the 1957 world championship tour (34%) and on the 1960 four man tour (56%).{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=205\u2013216|ps=}} In the 1959 Ampol world tournament series, Hoad's winning percentage was 71% (36/51) compared to Gonzales' 72% (26/36). Gonzales defaulted three Ampol tournaments and played 15 fewer matches than Hoad on the tour.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=211\u2013216|ps=}} For the 1959 season as a whole, Hoad was credited with a 24 to 23 edge in wins against Gonzales, a series consistency which surpasses any other opponent of Gonzales during his world champion years.<ref name=\"theage19600104\"/> Hoad's consistency on grass surfaces is highlighted by his lifetime edge in play against Gonzales on grass of 20 to 14 (59%).<ref>TennisBase, lifetime head-to-head stats / newspaper reports of 1961 British head-to-head tour</ref> Hoad trails Rosewall lifetime in grasscourt meetings, 18 to 26, Hoad's results declining after 1961.<ref name=\"hoad_rosewal_hth\">{{cite web|title=Ken Rosewall vs Lew Hoad Head 2 Head|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=ROSEWALL%2C+KEN&player_input=&sub=6&apartado=6&subH2H=1&player2_head=HOAD,%20LEW#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> Hoad was 14 wins and 18 losses against Rosewall lifetime in grass court tournament play,  Hoad was 8 wins and 10 losses lifetime on clay against Rosewall, and 11 wins and 11 losses lifetime on clay against Trabert.<ref name=\"hoad_rosewal_hth\"/><ref>Hoad/Trabert rivalries, TennisBase</ref> Lifetime on all surfaces, primarily indoor, Hoad trails Gonzales 77\u2013104 and trails Rosewall 51\u201384.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lew Hoad: Rivalries|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HOAD%2C+LEW&player_input=HOAD%2C+LEW&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> On outdoor surfaces, (grass, clay, and cement) Gonzales held a 36 to 31  lifetime edge over Hoad, or 53%.<ref>TennisBase 2017, hth rivalries</ref>\n\nOn the head-to-head world pro tours of the era, Hoad compiled 51 wins and 64 losses against Gonzales, the best head-to-head showing of any pro against the reigning champion Gonzales, and in spite of a three month period of substandard play during the 1958 season due to injury. On the 1959 Ampol world championship series of tournaments, Hoad's record was 3 wins and 5 losses against Gonzales<ref>{{cite web|title=Pancho Gonzales: Rivalries|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player1=GONZALES,%20PANCHO&sub=10&idjugador=46369#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|pp=211\u2013216|ps=}} However, Hoad was more consistent than Gonzales against the other ten players on the Ampol series, winning 33 of 43 matches (77%), while Gonzales won 21 of 28 (75%). Hoad won six tournaments compared to Gonzales' four, and he had 6 wins and 2 losses against Rosewall on the 1959 Ampol series, while Gonzales was 1 win and 3 losses against Rosewall. Hoad had a 15\u201313 edge over Gonzales in their meetings on the 4-man championship tour of 1959, but as Joe McCauley noted, Hoad was deprived of overall victory on this tour because he was less consistent than Gonzales when facing the rookie pros, [[Mal Anderson]] and [[Ashley Cooper (tennis)|Ashley Cooper]]. Hoad's combined record against the rookies was 27\u20137 compared to Gonzales\u2019 34\u20130.{{sfnp|McCauley|2000|p=92|ps=}}\n\nGonzales always maintained that Hoad was the toughest, most skillful adversary that he had ever faced.  \"''He was the only guy who, if I was playing my best tennis, could still beat me.''\" said Gonzales in a 1995 ''[[New York Times]]'' interview.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=62|ps=}}  \"''I think his game was the best game ever. Better than mine. He was capable of making more shots than anybody. His two volleys were great. His overhead was enormous. He had the most natural tennis mind with the most natural tennis physique.''\"<ref name=sahof/> In a 1970 interview he stated that \"''Hoad was probably the best and toughest player when he wanted to be. After the first two years on the tour, his back injury plagued him so much that he lost the desire to practice. He was the only man to beat me in a head-to-head tour, 15 to 13.''\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dave Anderson|title=Pancho Picks Hoad|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rAAzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=W-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7390%2C2313980|work=The Spokesman-Review|date=23 January 1970}}</ref> Kramer, however, had mixed feelings about Hoad's ability. In spite of calling him one of the 21 best players of all time, albeit in the second echelon, he also writes that \"''when you sum Hoad up, you have to say that he was overrated. He might have been the best, but day-to-day, week-to-week, he was the most inconsistent of all the top players.''\"{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|p=230|ps=}} In an interview for the Australian Sport Oral History Project, Rosewall explained that\n\"Hoad would play hard if it was a major, but if it was a minor, well...you weren't going to get much out of him.\"<ref>National Library of Australia, Sport Oral History Project, 2007, ID 4319211</ref>\nHoad himself made a similar remark in a 1984 interview in World Tennis, \"I would play hard in a major tournament final, but if it was the final of the Hamburger Open, against a player I knew I could beat, well..\", and he shrugged his shoulders.<ref>World Tennis, details forthcoming</ref>\n\nIn a 1963 article in ''World Tennis'' Rosewall judged Gonzales to be a notch above Hoad but stated that \"''...the latter is the greatest of all time when he is 'on'.''\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131720746 |title=Rosewall praises Gonzales. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=29 May 1963  |page=45 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> an opinion echoed by [[Frew McMillan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Golden Boy and good girls|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2001/jul/01/tennis.theobserver1|website=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=The Observer|date=1 July 2001}}</ref> In 2010, Rosewall rated Hoad at the top of his personal list of the top four greatest tennis players of all time, ahead of Gonzales, Laver, and Federer.<ref>\"Chasing Greatness: GOAT or GOATs?\". Tennis Pulse. Frangou, Nat. 22 June 2017.</ref> In 2007, Butch Buchholz rated Hoad as the greatest player of his era, but said he was \"injury prone and not exactly a model of fitness\". Buchholz stated that \"If you had an Earth vs. Mars match, and had to send one man to represent the planet, I would send Hoad.\"<ref name=\"bodo2007\"/> Buchholz had played the undercard matches on Hoad's 1961 British tour against Gonzales, and Hoad's 1963 Australian tour against Laver. In July, 1961, Gardnar Mulloy rated Hoad as the greatest player of the time, based on his results against Gonzales, and named Hoad as the favourite to win a prospective open Wimbledon.<ref>16 July 1961, Miami News</ref> Mulloy had beaten both Hoad and Gonzales in singles competition.\n\n[[Max Robertson]], tennis author and commentator, rated Hoad as the best post-war Wimbledon player, followed by Gonzales and Laver, in his 1977 book ''Wimbledon 1877\u20131977''.<ref name=\"robertson1977\">{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|authorlink=Max Robertson|title=Wimbledon 1877\u20131977|year=1977|publisher=Arthur Baker Limited|location=London|isbn=0213166437|page=164}}</ref>  In the second edition (1981) his list was unchanged but in the third edition (1987) he listed Hoad second behind [[Boris Becker]].<ref name=\"robertson1981\">{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|authorlink=Max Robertson|title=Wimbledon \u2013 Centre Court of the Game|year=1981|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=London|isbn=0563179236|page=307}}</ref><ref name=\"robertson1987\">{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|authorlink=Max Robertson|title=Wimbledon - Centre Court of the Game|year=1987|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|location=London|isbn=0563204540|page=463}}</ref> In ''The Encyclopedia of Tennis'' (1973) sportswriters [[Allison Danzig]] and [[Lance Tingay]] as well as tennis coach and former player [[Harry Hopman]] listed their ten greatest players. Only Tingay included Hoad in his list, ranking him in fifth position.<ref name=\"robertson1974\">{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|authorlink=Max Robertson|title=The Encyclopedia of Tennis|year=1974|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|isbn=9780047960420|page=175}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[100 Greatest of All Time]]'', a 2012 television series broadcast by the Tennis Channel, Hoad was ranked the 19th greatest male player. With his movie-star good looks, powerful physique, and outgoing personality, Hoad became a tennis icon in the 1950s. As Kramer says, \"Everybody loved Hoad, even [[Pancho Gonzales]]. They should put that on Lew's tombstone as the ultimate praise for the man.... Even when Hoad was clobbering Gonzales, Gorgo wanted his respect and friendship.\"{{sfnp|Kramer|1981|p=201|ps=}} In a 1975 issue of [[Sports Illustrated]], [[Arthur Ashe]] was quoted as relating a remark which Pancho Gonzales had said to him, \"If there was ever a Universe Davis Cup, and I had to pick one man to represent Planet Earth, I would pick Lew Hoad in his prime.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author1=Arthur Ashe |author2=Frank Deford |title=A shout for those Aussies |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=10 March 1975 |volume=42 |issue=10 |page=45 |url=https://www.si.com/vault/issue/43266/47}}</ref>\n\n[[Rod Laver]] in 2012 rated Hoad as the greatest player of the 'past champions' era of tennis. Laver described his strengths of \"power, volleying and explosiveness\" as justification of his accolade.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rod Laver's 10 best past and present players|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/archive/old-sport-pages/photos-fn77kxzt-1226250654969?page=11|work=[[Herald-Sun]]|date=2012}}</ref> In a January 2019 interview, Laver stated that Hoad was \"the best player who ever held a racquet. He had every shot in the book and he could overpower anyone. He was so strong.\" <ref>Laver interview with Grantlee Kieza in the \"Courier Mail\", 26 January 2019</ref>  Pancho Gonzales made a similar assessment, \"He was such a strong son****...when he tried, you just couldn't beat him. He hit the ball harder than anyone I ever played.\"<ref>Anderson, N.Y. Times, 1995</ref>{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=234|ps=}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Lew Hoad Jennifer Staley.jpg|thumb|Lew Hoad and [[Jenny Staley Hoad|Jennifer Staley]] (right) at the Davis Cup Ball on 30 December 1953]]\nHoad proposed to his girlfriend, Australian tennis player [[Jenny Staley Hoad|Jenny Staley]], on her 21st birthday party in March 1955 and they planned to announce their engagement in June in London while both were on an overseas tour.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=28|ps=}} After arrival in London Jenny discovered that she was pregnant and the couple decided to get married straight away.{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|pp=29\u201332|ps=}} The marriage took place the following day on 18 June 1955 at [[St Mary's Church, Wimbledon]] in London on the eve of Wimbledon fortnight.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71889118 |title=2-day honeymoon-then tennis.|newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=20 June 1955 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tennis Star Takes Bride In London|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_AYrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TpgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1393%2C837681|work=Reading Eagle \u2013 June 19, 1955|date=19 June 1955}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71669227 |title=My Wimbledon romance. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=23 July 1955 |page=33 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They have two daughters and a son.\n\nAfter announcing his retirement in 1967, due to persistent back problems, Hoad moved to [[Fuengirola]], Spain, near [[M\u00e1laga]], where he and his wife operated a tennis resort, ''Lew Hoad's Campo de Tenis'', for more than thirty years entertaining personal friends such as actors [[Stewart Granger]], [[Sean Connery]], [[Deborah Kerr]] and her husband  writer [[Peter Viertel]], actor [[Kirk Douglas]], and saxophonist [[Stan Getz]].<ref name=theage19670609/><ref name=ww1974>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article0 |title=After seven years in Spain Lew Hoad now feels... |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | date=10 April 1974  |page=17 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48211276 |title=Luxury \"Campo de Tennis\". |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | date=11 June 1969 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|pp=120\u2013126|ps=}}\n\nIn 1978, Hoad's back problem was successfully treated with spinal fusion surgery, and he was relieved of pain. There had been two ruptured discs and a herniation. The doctor asked one of Hoad's friends, \"How on earth did this man walk, let alone play tennis?\"{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|pp=220, 221|ps=}}\n\nHoad was diagnosed with a rare and incurable form of [[leukemia]] on 13 January 1994 which caused his death on 3 July 1994. Press reports of a heart attack were incorrect. Hoad's personal physician specialist was his own son-in-law Dr. Manuel Benavides, who explained the cause of death.{{sfnp|Hodgson|Jones|2001|p=222|ps=}}{{sfnp|Hoad|2002|p=193}}<ref name=nyt19940705>{{cite news|title=Lew Hoad, 59, Tennis Champion of the 1950's|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/05/obituaries/lew-hoad-59-tennis-champion-of-the-1950-s.html|work=The New York Times|date=5 July 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118188847 |title=Tennis legend Lew Hoad dies. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=5 July 1994  |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A book co-written with Jack Pollard and titled ''My Game'' (\"The Lew Hoad story\" in the USA) was published in 1958. In 2002, Pollard teamed up with his widow, Jenny, to write ''My Life With Lew''.\n\nHoad was inducted into the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], in 1980 and this was followed in December 1985 by his induction into the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame Awards|Sport Australia Hall of Fame]].<ref name=sahof/> In January 1995 he was posthumously inducted into the Tennis Australia Hall of Fame together with friend and rival [[Ken Rosewall]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article127258752 |title=Hoad and Rosewall for Hall of Fame. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=6 December 1994 |page=29 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The [[International Tennis Federation|ITF]] organizes a seniors tournament in his honor called ''The Lew Hoad Memorial ITF Veterans Tournament''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Lew Hoad Memorial ITF Veterans Tournament|url=http://www.itftennis.com/seniors/tournaments/tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1100028220|publisher=ITF}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Kooyong Classic]] at [[Kooyong Stadium]], the principal warm-up event for the Australian Open, awards the Lew Hoad Memorial Trophy to the winner of the men's singles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pablo Carreno Busta beats Matthew Ebden to win Kooyong |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/tennis/pablo-carreno-busta-beats-matthew-ebden-to-win-kooyong/news-story/0e0b8031368dcd4961ea56275abda0c9 |website=[[The Australian]] |date=12 January 2018}}</ref> Kooyong stadium was the site of some of Hoad's greatest victories.\n\n==Grand Slam and Pro Slam finals==\n\n===Singles===\n\n====Grand Slam finals (4\u20132)====\n{| class='sortable wikitable' \n!style=\"width:45px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:175px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:170px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n|style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||[[1955 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1955]]||[[Australian Open|Australian Championships]]||Grass||{{Flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]||7\u20139, 4\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n|style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win ||[[1956 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]]||[[Australian Open|Australian Championships]]||Grass||{{Flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]||6\u20134, 3\u20136, 6\u20134, 7\u20135\n|-style=\"background:#ebc2af;\"\n|style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win ||[[1956 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1956]]||[[French Open|French Championships]]||Clay||{{Flagicon|SWE}} [[Sven Davidson]]||6\u20134, 8\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n