hampionships \u2013 Men's Singles|F]]\n|  colspan=\"11\"| ''not eligible''\n|  A\n|  A\n|  A\n|  A\n|  A\n|  bgcolor=efefef |0 / 5\n|  bgcolor=efefef |21\u20135\n|  bgcolor=efefef |81%\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=23|[[Major professional tennis tournaments before the Open Era|Pro Slam tournaments]] !! 0 / 22 !! 30\u201322 !! 58%\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" bgcolor=efefef |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships|U.S. Pro]]\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1958|F]]\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1959|F]]\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1963|QF]]\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1964|QF]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1946\u20131967#1966|QF]]\n| A\n| rowspan=3 colspan=5|\n| bgcolor=efefef |0 / 5\n| bgcolor=efefef |6\u20135\n| bgcolor=efefef |55%\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" bgcolor=efefef|[[French Pro Championship|French Pro]]\n| NH\n| NH\n| NH\n| NH\n| NH\n| A\n| NH\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1958|F]]\n| bgcolor=yellow  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1959|SF]]\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1960|F]]\n| bgcolor=afeeee  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1961|1R]]\n| bgcolor=afeeee  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1962|1R]]\n| bgcolor=yellow  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1963|SF]]\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1964|QF]]\n| A\n| A\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[French Pro Championship Draws#1967|QF]]\n| bgcolor=efefef |0 / 8\n| bgcolor=efefef |12\u20138\n| bgcolor=efefef |60%\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" bgcolor=efefef|{{nowrap|[[Wembley Championship|Wembley Pro]]}}\n| A\n| A\n| A\n| NH\n| NH\n| A\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1957|QF]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1959|QF]]\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1960|QF]]\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1961|F]]\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1962|F]]\n| bgcolor=thistle |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1963|F]]\n| bgcolor=ffebcd  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1964|QF]]\n| A\n| bgcolor=yellow  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1966|SF]]\n| bgcolor=afeeee  |[[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1967|1R]]\n| bgcolor=efefef |0 / 9\n| bgcolor=efefef |12\u20139\n| bgcolor=efefef |57%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" bgcolor=efefef|'''Win\u2013Loss'''\n| 1\u20131\n| 8\u20134\n| 13\u20134\n| 10\u20133\n| 12\u20133\n| 24\u20131\n| 10\u20133\n| 5\u20132\n| 5\u20133\n| 3\u20132\n| 3\u20132\n| 3\u20132\n| 5\u20133\n| 2\u20133\n|  0\u20130\n| 3\u20132\n| 1\u20132\n| 2\u20131\n|  0\u20130\n| 4\u20132\n|  0\u20130\n|  0\u20131\n| bgcolor=efefef |{{nowrap|'''4 / 48'''}}\n| bgcolor=efefef |{{nowrap|'''114\u201344'''}}\n| bgcolor=efefef |{{nowrap|'''72%'''}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Overall tennis records \u2013 Men's Singles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Davidson|first=Owen|title=Lawn Tennis : The Great Ones|year=1970|publisher=Pelham Books|location=London|isbn=9780720703801|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kramer|first=Jack|title=The Game : My 40 Years in Tennis|year=1981|publisher=Deutsch|location=London|isbn=0233973079|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCauley|first=Joe|title=The History of Professional Tennis|year=2000|publisher=The Short Run Book Company Limited|location=Windsor|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Biographies\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Hoad|first1=Lew|last2=Pollard|first2=Jack|title=The Lew Hoad Story|year=1958|publisher=Prentice-Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs|oclc=398749|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hodgson|first1=Larry|last2=Jones|first2=Dudley|title=Golden Boy : The Life and Times of Lew Hoad, A Tennis Legend|year=2001|publisher=DSM|location=Denton, Peterborough|isbn=978-0953651641|ol=9512749M|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hoad|first1=Jenny|last2=Pollard|first2=Jack|title=My Life with Lew|year=2002|publisher=HarperSports|location=Australia|isbn=9780732270674|oclc=49551342|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=162639|n=no|b=no|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|species=no|m=no|mw=no|q=no|c=Category:Lew Hoad}}\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF profile}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n* {{Tennis Hall of Fame}}\n* {{Tennis Australia}}\n* Hoad vs. Rosewall, 1955 NSW final, White City, Sydney-newsreel [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eZuHFIljKzQ]\n*  Hoad vs. Sirola, 1956 German final, Hamburg, at 8:20-newsreel [https://www.filmothek.bundesarchiv.de/video/584192?set_land=de]\n* Hoad df. Rosewall, 1959 Roland Garros 3rd place-newsreel [https://www.ina.fr/video/I05278576/yul-brynner-a-roland-garros-video.html]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141028045443/http://www.lew-hoad.com/en/history/ Lew Hoad Tennis and Paddle Club]\n\n{{Tennis men grand slam two and over}}\n{{Tennis Career Grand Slam Champions}}\n{{navboxes|title=Lew Hoad in the [[grand slam (tennis)|Grand Slam Tournaments]]\n|list1=\n{{Australian Open men's singles champions}}\n{{French Open men's singles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon men's singles champions}}\n{{Australian Championships men's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open men's doubles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon men's doubles champions}}\n{{U.S. National Championships Men's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open mixed doubles champions}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoad, Lew}}\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) junior champions]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:Australian male tennis players]]\n[[Category:French Championships (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:People from Fuengirola]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:International Tennis Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:United States National champions (tennis)]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon champions (pre-Open Era)]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's doubles]]\n[[Category:Deaths from leukemia]]\n[[Category:Professional tennis players before the Open Era]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' doubles]]\n", "name_user": "Tennisedu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssessment:Tennisedu/punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lew_Hoad"}
{"title_page": "Willa Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[U.S. Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = January 22, 1906\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil Rights]] Leader, first African American Officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], first African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = Wilbur Hardaway<br>[[Cornelius Coffey]]<br>Rev. J. H. Chappell\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], the first African American officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], and the first woman in the United States to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> A lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in flight and in the military, Brown not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps|U.S. Army Air Corp]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Cornelius Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy in the United States owned and operated by African Americans. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWell after the Coffey School closed in 1945, Brown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]]. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref> \n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to [[Chicago]], where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69-71}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilot's Association,\na group of African-American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic, at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field. She also began taking classes at [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]].<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49-52|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned her private pilot's license in 1938 and her commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn a commercial pilot's license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 |author=Editorial Board | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|Sources disagree on whether she was the first African-American woman to earn any kind of pilot's license or the first to earn a commercial license; see <ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> and <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" />.}} Later, Brown and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nTogether with Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters, Willa Brown helped form the National Airmen's Association of America in 1939, whose main goal was to get black aviation cadets into the United States military. As the organization's national secretary and the president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. \n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe continually lobbied the government for integration of black pilots into the segregated Army Air Corps and the federal Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), the system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. Subsequently, when Congress finally voted to allow separate-but-equal participation of blacks in civilian flight training programs, the Coffey School of Aeronautics was chosen for participation in the CPTP.\n\nBrown became the coordinator for the CPTP in Chicago. Later, her flight school was also selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program at the Tuskegee Institute.<ref name=\"cap-bio\"/>\n\nWilla Brown eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority and later was a member of the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Board. She was the first black female officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African-American woman to in a Congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 1971, Brown was appointed to the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, the first black woman serving on the committee. She served on the committee until 1974.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans />\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further Reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[U.S. Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = January 22, 1906\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil Rights]] Leader, first African American Officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], first African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = Wilbur Hardaway<br>[[Cornelius Coffey]]<br>Rev. J. H. Chappell\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], the first African American officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], and the first woman in the United States to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> A lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in flight and in the military, Brown not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps|U.S. Army Air Corp]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Cornelius Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy in the United States owned and operated by African Americans. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWell after the Coffey School closed in 1945, Brown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]]. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref> \n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to [[Chicago]], where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69-71}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilot's Association,\na group of African-American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic, at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field. She also began taking classes at [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]].<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49-52|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned her private pilot's license in 1938 and her commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn a commercial pilot's license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 |author=Editorial Board | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|Sources disagree on whether she was the first African-American woman to earn any kind of pilot's license or the first to earn a commercial license; see <ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> and <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" />.}} Later, Brown and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nTogether with Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters, Willa Brown helped form the National Airmen's Association of America in 1939, whose main goal was to get black aviation cadets into the United States military. As the organization's national secretary and the president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. \n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe continually lobbied the government for integration of black pilots into the segregated Army Air Corps and the federal Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), the system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. Subsequently, when Congress finally voted to allow separate-but-equal participation of blacks in civilian flight training programs, the Coffey School of Aeronautics was chosen for participation in the CPTP.\n\nBrown became the coordinator for the CPTP in Chicago. Later, her flight school was also selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program at the Tuskegee Institute.<ref name=\"cap-bio\"/>\n\nWilla Brown eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority and later was a member of the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Board. She was the first black female officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African-American woman to in a Congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 1971, Brown was appointed to the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, the first black woman serving on the committee. She served on the committee until 1974.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans />\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"{{notelist-la}}\" />\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further Reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n", "name_user": "Creffett", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and recognition:epic copy-paste fail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willa_Brown"}
{"title_page": "Feeding the Machine (Wolf album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} \n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Feeding the Machine\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Wolf (band)|Wolf]]\n<!-- Commented out: | cover      = WOLF Feeding The Machine.jpg -->\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 13, 2020\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[power metal]]\n| length     = 46:54\n| label      = [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n| producer   = Simon Johansson\n| prev_title = [[Devil Seed]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|8|10|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/reviews/wolf-feeding-the-machine|title=WOLF - Feeding The Machine|last=Gromen|first=Mark|date=March 29, 2020|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| rev2 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev2score = {{rating|3.5|5|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/soundoff.php?albumid=344396|title=Wolf   Feeding the Machine|last=|first=|date=|website=Sputnikmusic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| rev3 = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n| rev3score = {{rating|8|10|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/feeding-the-machine/|title=WOLF \"Feeding The Machine\"|last=Lawson|first=Dom|date=|website=Blabbermouth|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Feeding the Machine''''' is the eighth studio album by Swedish [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Wolf (band)|Wolf]], released on 13 March 2020 via Century Media Records. It is the first album featuring band's new members, Johan Koleberg on drums and Pontus Egberg on bass guitar. The album is being produced by Wolf's Simon Johansson at SolnaSound Production and mixed and mastered by Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m of Studio Fredman. <ref name=\"BW1\">{{cite web |title=WOLF To Release Feeding The Machine Album In March; New Band Members Introduced |url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-to-release-feeding-the-machine-album-in-march-new-band-members-introduced |website=Bravewords.com |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WOLF Joined By KING DIAMOND Bassist, Ex-HAMMERFALL Drummer |url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-joined-by-king-diamond-bassist-ex-hammerfall-drummer/ |website=Blabbermouth|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn an interview in December 2018, Niklas St\u00e5lvind revealed that the band is working on a new album and they want to get back to the roots of the old school Wolf. He stated that the album will have ten or twelve songs but he was not sure about the release date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2018/12/22/interview-with-niklas-stalvind-wolf-the-plan-is-to-release-the-new-album-in-august/|title=Interview With Niklas St\u00e5lvind, WOLF: \u201cThe plan is to release the new album in August\u201d|last=|first=|date=December 22, 2018|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\nOn 30 September 2019, Wolf announced the separation of Modd and Holmgren from the band and revealed the new line up featuring [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]] bass payer, Pontus Egberg and ex[[Hammerfall]] drummer, Johan Koleberg. The band also revealed the title and release date of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-joined-by-king-diamond-bassist-ex-hammerfall-drummer/|title=WOLF Joined By KING DIAMOND Bassist, Ex-HAMMERFALL Drummer|last=|first=|date=September 30, 2019|website=Blabbermouth|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-to-release-feeding-the-machine-album-in-march-new-band-members-introduced|title=WOLF To Release Feeding The Machine Album In March; New Band Members Introduced|last=|first=|date=September 30, 2019|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In another interview with Mohsen Stargazer Fayazi of Metal Shock Finland on 8 October 2019, St\u00e5lvind explains why it took them longer to bring their new album to the light, he stated that he wrote the first song for this album in 2015 but mainly because all members of the band were busy with their full jobs they were not able to make it faster. Then he explained the concept and idea behind the title of the album which is the role and affection of social networks on people's normal life and minds. He explains: \"''When I was unemployed, I used social media to sell my artworks...But around 2016, I started to noticed, what the f*ck is this, it\u2019s not me using Facebook anymore, it\u2019s Facebook using me. It\u2019s so manipulative and it just make people gather in small groups hating each other and I felt something is really wrong there.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2019/10/08/interview-with-niklas-wolf/|title=Interview With WOLF\u2019s Niklas St\u00e5lvind: \u201cWe Are All Feeding This Machine!\u201d|last=|first=|date=October 8, 2019|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 December 2019, Wolf announced tour dates with [[Grand Magus]], including eighteen shows in the UK, France, Netherlands and Germany which were later canceled after their show in London duo to [[COVID-19 epidemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nuclearblast.de/en/label/music/band/news/details/6405145.730950.grand-magus-announce-039-wolf-god-039-tour.html|title=GRAND MAGUS - Announce Their Return to Europe For 'Wolf God' Tour In 2020!|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2019|website=Nuclear Blast|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wolf.nu/index2.php|title=European leg of our tour with Grand Magus is postponed|last=|first=|date= March 13, 2020|website=WOLF official website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe band revealed artwork and track-listing for the album on January 10, 2020, including twelve tracks and a cover version of [[Angel Witch]]'s  'Atlanta' single as a bonus track on the Limited Edition CD Digipak and also on the CD coming along with the LP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-reveal-artwork-tracklisting-for-upcoming-feeding-the-machine-album|title=WOLF Reveal Artwork, Tracklisting For Upcoming Feeding The Machine Album|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWolf released a video clip for 'Midnight Hour' single on January 19 2020, the video was directed by Daniel Wahlstr\u00f6m and it is the first appearance of the band's new members, Johan Koleberg and Pontus Egberg on a video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-releases-midnight-hour-music-video/|title=WOLF Releases 'Midnight Hour' Music Video|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2020|website=Blabbermouth|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> on February 14 the same year, band posted a lyric video for \u2018Shoot to Kill\u2019 single, the video was produced by Iranian metal man Mohsen \u201cStargazer\u201d Fayazi. Niklas comments on the single: \"''Fist waving, fast and straight up in-your-face-metal in the classic WOLF vein. Perfect for banging your head''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/events/news_comments.php?news_id=37715|title=Wolf - Release Second Single And Lyric Video|last=|first=|date=February 16, 2020|website=Metalstorm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2020/02/14/wolf-post-new-lyric-video-online-shoot-to-kill/|title=WOLF: Post New Lyric Video Online; \u2018Shoot To Kill\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 14, 2020|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The third single of the band was released with a video for the title track of the album on March 6, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-premier-feeding-the-machine-music-video|title=WOLF Premier \"Feeding The Machine\" Music Video|last=|first=|date=March 6, 2020|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n<small>'''* All Lyrics were written by Niklas St\u00e5lvind'''</small>\n{{Tracklist\n| total_length = 46:54\n| title1 = Shoot to Kill \n| writer1 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length1 = 3:41\n| title2 = Guillotine\n| writer2 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length2 = 4:04\n| title3 = Dead Man\u2019s Hand\n| writer3 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length3 = 3:09\n| title4 = Midnight Hour\n| writer4 = St\u00e5lvind, Johansson\n| length4 = 3:22\n| title5 = Mass Confusion\n| writer5 = St\u00e5lvind,Johansson, Modd\n| length5 = 4:12\n| title6 =  The Cold Emptiness\n| writer6 = Johansson\n| length6 = 3:48\n| title7 = Feeding the Machine\n| writer7 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length7 = 3:51\n| title8 = Devil in the Flesh\n| writer8 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length8 = 3:18\n| title9 = Spoon Bender\n| writer9 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = The Raven\n| writer10 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length10 = 4:29\n| title11 = Black Widow\n| writer11 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length11 = 4:00\n| title12 = A Thief Inside\n| writer12 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length12 = 5:34\n|}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Band'''\n* Niklas St\u00e5lvind \u2013 vocals, guitar\n* Simon Johansson \u2013 guitar\n* Pontus Egberg \u2013 bass guitar\n* Johan Koleberg \u2013 drums\n\n===Other personnel===\n* Produced by Simon Johansson\n* Mixed and mastered by Fredrick Nordst\u00f6rm\n* Engineered by Simon Johansson and Mike Wead\n* Artwork by Thomas Holm\n* Photography by Ther\u00e9s Bj\u00f6rk\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wolf (band)}}\n\n[[Category:Century Media Records albums]]\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Wolf (band) albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} \n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Feeding the Machine\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Wolf (band)|Wolf]]\n<!-- Commented out: | cover      = WOLF Feeding The Machine.jpg -->\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 13, 2020\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[power metal]]\n| length     = 46:54\n| label      = [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n| producer   = Simon Johansson\n| prev_title = [[Devil Seed]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|8|10|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/reviews/wolf-feeding-the-machine|title=WOLF - Feeding The Machine|last=Gromen|first=Mark|date=March 29, 2020|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| rev2 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev2score = {{rating|3.5|5|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/soundoff.php?albumid=344396|title=Wolf   Feeding the Machine|last=|first=|date=|website=Sputnikmusic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| rev3 = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n| rev3score = {{rating|8|10|}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/feeding-the-machine/|title=WOLF\n\"Feeding The Machine\"|last=Lawson|first=Dom|date=|website=Blabbermouth.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Feeding the Machine''''' is the eighth studio album by Swedish [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Wolf (band)|Wolf]], released on 13 March 2020 via Century Media Records. It is the first album featuring band's new members, Johan Koleberg on drums and Pontus Egberg on bass guitar. The album is being produced by Wolf's Simon Johansson at SolnaSound Production and mixed and mastered by Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m of Studio Fredman. <ref name=\"BW1\">{{cite web |title=WOLF To Release Feeding The Machine Album In March; New Band Members Introduced |url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-to-release-feeding-the-machine-album-in-march-new-band-members-introduced |website=Bravewords.com |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WOLF Joined By KING DIAMOND Bassist, Ex-HAMMERFALL Drummer |url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-joined-by-king-diamond-bassist-ex-hammerfall-drummer/ |website=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn an interview in December 2018, Niklas St\u00e5lvind revealed that the band is working on a new album and they want to get back to the roots of the old school Wolf. He stated that the album will have ten or twelve songs but he was not sure about the release date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2018/12/22/interview-with-niklas-stalvind-wolf-the-plan-is-to-release-the-new-album-in-august/|title=Interview With Niklas St\u00e5lvind, WOLF: \u201cThe plan is to release the new album in August\u201d|last=|first=|date=December 22, 2018|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\nOn 30 September 2019, Wolf announced the separation of Modd and Holmgren from the band and revealed the new line up featuring [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]] bass payer, Pontus Egberg and ex[[Hammerfall]] drummer, Johan Koleberg. The band also revealed the title and release date of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-joined-by-king-diamond-bassist-ex-hammerfall-drummer/|title=WOLF Joined By KING DIAMOND Bassist, Ex-HAMMERFALL Drummer|last=|first=|date=September 30, 2019|website=Blabbermouth|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-to-release-feeding-the-machine-album-in-march-new-band-members-introduced|title=WOLF To Release Feeding The Machine Album In March; New Band Members Introduced|last=|first=|date=September 30, 2019|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In another interview with Mohsen Stargazer Fayazi of Metal Shock Finland on 8 October 2019, St\u00e5lvind explains why it took them longer to bring their new album to the light, he stated that he wrote the first song for this album in 2015 but mainly because all members of the band were busy with their full jobs they were not able to make it faster. Then he explained the concept and idea behind the title of the album which is the role and affection of social networks on people's normal life and minds. He explains: \"''When I was unemployed, I used social media to sell my artworks...But around 2016, I started to noticed, what the f*ck is this, it\u2019s not me using Facebook anymore, it\u2019s Facebook using me. It\u2019s so manipulative and it just make people gather in small groups hating each other and I felt something is really wrong there.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2019/10/08/interview-with-niklas-wolf/|title=Interview With WOLF\u2019s Niklas St\u00e5lvind: \u201cWe Are All Feeding This Machine!\u201d|last=|first=|date=October 8, 2019|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 December 2019, Wolf announced tour dates with [[Grand Magus]], including eighteen shows in the UK, France, Netherlands and Germany which were later canceled after their show in London duo to [[COVID-19 epidemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nuclearblast.de/en/label/music/band/news/details/6405145.730950.grand-magus-announce-039-wolf-god-039-tour.html|title=GRAND MAGUS - Announce Their Return to Europe For 'Wolf God' Tour In 2020!|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2019|website=Nuclear Blast|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wolf.nu/index2.php|title=European leg of our tour with Grand Magus is postponed|last=|first=|date= March 13, 2020|website=WOLF official website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe band revealed artwork and track-listing for the album on January 10, 2020, including twelve tracks and a cover version of [[Angel Witch]]'s  'Atlanta' single as a bonus track on the Limited Edition CD Digipak and also on the CD coming along with the LP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-reveal-artwork-tracklisting-for-upcoming-feeding-the-machine-album|title=WOLF Reveal Artwork, Tracklisting For Upcoming Feeding The Machine Album|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWolf released a video clip for 'Midnight Hour' single on January 19 2020, the video was directed by Daniel Wahlstr\u00f6m and it is the first appearance of the band's new members, Johan Koleberg and Pontus Egberg on a video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/wolf-releases-midnight-hour-music-video/|title=WOLF Releases 'Midnight Hour' Music Video|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2020|website=Blabbermouth|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> on February 14 the same year, band posted a lyric video for \u2018Shoot to Kill\u2019 single, the video was produced by Iranian metal man Mohsen \u201cStargazer\u201d Fayazi. Niklas comments on the single: \"''Fist waving, fast and straight up in-your-face-metal in the classic WOLF vein. Perfect for banging your head''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/events/news_comments.php?news_id=37715|title=Wolf - Release Second Single And Lyric Video|last=|first=|date=February 16, 2020|website=Metalstorm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2020/02/14/wolf-post-new-lyric-video-online-shoot-to-kill/|title=WOLF: Post New Lyric Video Online; \u2018Shoot To Kill\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 14, 2020|website=Metal Shock Finland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The third single of the band was released with a video for the title track of the album on March 6, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/wolf-premier-feeding-the-machine-music-video|title=WOLF Premier \"Feeding The Machine\" Music Video|last=|first=|date=March 6, 2020|website=Bravewords|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n<small>'''* All Lyrics were written by Niklas St\u00e5lvind'''</small>\n{{Tracklist\n| total_length = 46:54\n| title1 = Shoot to Kill \n| writer1 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length1 = 3:41\n| title2 = Guillotine\n| writer2 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length2 = 4:04\n| title3 = Dead Man\u2019s Hand\n| writer3 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length3 = 3:09\n| title4 = Midnight Hour\n| writer4 = St\u00e5lvind, Johansson\n| length4 = 3:22\n| title5 = Mass Confusion\n| writer5 = St\u00e5lvind,Johansson, Modd\n| length5 = 4:12\n| title6 =  The Cold Emptiness\n| writer6 = Johansson\n| length6 = 3:48\n| title7 = Feeding the Machine\n| writer7 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length7 = 3:51\n| title8 = Devil in the Flesh\n| writer8 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length8 = 3:18\n| title9 = Spoon Bender\n| writer9 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = The Raven\n| writer10 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length10 = 4:29\n| title11 = Black Widow\n| writer11 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length11 = 4:00\n| title12 = A Thief Inside\n| writer12 = St\u00e5lvind\n| length12 = 5:34\n|}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Band'''\n* Niklas St\u00e5lvind \u2013 vocals, guitar\n* Simon Johansson \u2013 guitar\n* Pontus Egberg \u2013 bass guitar\n* Johan Koleberg \u2013 drums\n\n===Other personnel===\n* Produced by Simon Johansson\n* Mixed and mastered by Fredrick Nordst\u00f6rm\n* Engineered by Simon Johansson and Mike Wead\n* Artwork by Thomas Holm\n* Photography by Ther\u00e9s Bj\u00f6rk\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wolf (band)}}\n\n[[Category:Century Media Records albums]]\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Wolf (band) albums]]\n", "name_user": "User-duck", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove linefeed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feeding_the_Machine_(Wolf_album)"}
{"title_page": "Lawrence Montaigne", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{ Infobox person\n| name         = Lawrence Montaigne\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1931|2|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brooklyn, New York]], United States\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2017|3|17|1931|2|26}}\n| death_place  = [[Henderson, Nevada]], United States\n| occupation   = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive  = 1953\u20132007\n}}\n\n'''Lawrence Montaigne''' (February 26, 1931 \u2013 March 17, 2017) was an [[United States|American]] actor, writer, dancer, and stuntman.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Lawrence Montaigne|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/50094/Lawrence-Montaigne/filmography}}</ref> As an actor, he was known for his appearances on many 1960s-era television shows.<ref name=NYT />\n\n== Life and career ==\nBorn in New York, but later raised in [[Rome, Italy]], Montaigne spoke several languages - a skill he used to his advantage in securing roles in international productions. He served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and was only one platoon apart in the [[Parris Island]] [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|boot camp]] from his future friend [[Steve McQueen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreatescapelocations.com/Lawrence%20Montaigne.htm|title=New Page 1|work=thegreatescapelocations.com}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in the role of Dr. Chauncy Hartlund in the 1965 ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' episode, \"The Case of the Carefree Coronary.\" In 1966, Montaigne portrayed the [[Romulan]] Decius in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"[[Balance of Terror]]\"; he had nearly been cast as Mr Spock when it was possible that [[Leonard Nimoy]] would appear on ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission Impossible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/as-we-see-it/weekly-qa/2012/aug/08/man-who-would-be-spock/|title=The Man who would be Spock|author=Ken Miller|date=8 August 2012|work=LasVegasWeekly.com}}</ref> A year later, he portrayed the [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]] [[Stonn]], the [[Intimate relationship|paramour]] of [[Spock]]'s intended bride [[T'Pring]], in the episode \"[[Amok Time]]\"\u2014a role that he reprised in 2006 in the unofficial mini-series ''[[Star Trek: Of Gods and Men]]''.\n\nAdditionally, he guest-starred on ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'', ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'', ''[[The Man From U.N.C.L.E.]]'', ''[[Blue Light (TV series)|Blue Light]]'', ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission: Impossible]]'', ''[[The Time Tunnel]]'', ''[[The Invaders]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'', ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]'', [[List of Bonanza episodes|''Bonanza'']] and ''[[The Feather and Father Gang]]''.\n\nHis motion picture appearances include roles in ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' (1963),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Captain Sindbad]]'' (1963), ''[[Tobruk (1967 film)|Tobruk]]'' (1967), ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968), ''The Psycho Lover'' (1970), ''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]'' (1975),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Framed (1975 film)|Framed]]'' (1975), ''[[Young Lady Chatterley]]'' (1977),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Deadly Blessing]]'' (1981)<ref name=NYT /> and ''[[Dakota (1988 film)|Dakota]]'' (1988).<ref name=NYT /> During the 1980s, Montaigne taught film at [[North Texas State University]].\n\nFor some years, Montaigne lived in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], and translated medical texts for a publishing firm. In 2007, Montaigne voiced a guest-starring role in the pilot episode of the web series ''[[Star Trek: The Continuing Mission]]''.\n\nMontaigne died on March 17, 2017, at the age of 86.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/remembering-lawrence-montaigne-1931-2017|title=Remembering Lawrence Montaigne, 1931\u20132017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Selected television appearances ==\n* ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', episode \"The Case of the Carefree Coronary\" as Dr. Chauncy Hartlund (1965)\n* ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'', episode \"[[Balance of Terror]]\" as Decius (1966)\n* ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'', episode \"[[Amok Time]]\" as Stonn (1967)\n*[[List of Bonanza episodes|''Bonanza'']], episode \"Search in Limbo\" as Sid Langley (1972)\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Beast from 20,000 Fathoms]]'' || Soldier || Uncredited\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Band Wagon]]'' || Minor Role || Uncredited\n|-\n|1959|| ''Amud Ha'Esh'' || David ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''Rapina al quartiere Ovest'' || ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''Mobby Jackson'' || ||\n|-\n|1961|| ''[[The Mongols (film)|The Mongols]]'' || Prince Stefan's ally ||\n|-\n|1961|| ''[[The Italian Brigands]]'' || O Prevete ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[Damon and Pythias (film)|Damon and Pythias]]'' || Flute Player ||\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[Captain Sindbad]]'' || Jafar ||\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' || Haynes, \"Diversions\" ||\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[Combat!]]'' || Sgt. Koch || Episode: A Rare Vintage\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[The Satan Bug]]'' || Officer at Radar Tracking Station || Uncredited\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Synanon (film)|Synanon]]'' || The Greek ||\n|-\n|1967|| ''[[Tobruk (1967 film)|Tobruk]]'' || Italian Officer ||\n|-\n|1968|| ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' || Briggs ||\n|-\n|1969|| ''[[Topaz (1969 film)|Topaz]]'' || Russian Agent #2 || Uncredited\n|-\n|1970|| ''The Psycho Lover'' || Kenneth Alden ||\n|-\n|1971|| ''[[Bearcats!]]'' || Koster || 1 episode\n|-\n|1975|| ''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]'' || Ubermann ||\n|-\n|1975|| ''[[Framed (1975 film)|Framed]]'' || Deputy Allison ||\n|-\n|1977|| ''[[Young Lady Chatterley]]'' || Carl \u2013 Chauffeur ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Everything Happens to Me (1980 film)|Everything Happens to Me]]'' || Military Sergeant ||\n|-\n|1981|| ''[[Deadly Blessing]]'' || Matthew Gluntz ||\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[Dakota (1988 film)|Dakota]]'' || Mr. Diamond ||\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0598807}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=134149|name=Lawrence Montaigne}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lawrencemontaigne.com/|Montaigne's Web}}  Lawrence Montaigne's Personal Website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Montaigne, Lawrence}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:American translators]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American stunt performers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{ Infobox person\n| name         = Lawrence Montaigne\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1931|2|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brooklyn, New York]], United States\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2017|3|17|1931|2|26}}\n| death_place  = [[Henderson, Nevada]], United States\n| occupation   = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive  = 1953\u20132007\n}}\n\n'''Lawrence Montaigne''' (February 26, 1931 \u2013 March 17, 2017) was an [[United States|American]] actor, writer, dancer, and stuntman.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Lawrence Montaigne|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/50094/Lawrence-Montaigne/filmography}}</ref> As an actor, he was known for his appearances on many 1960s-era television shows.<ref name=NYT />\n\n== Life and career ==\nBorn in New York, but later raised in [[Rome, Italy]], Montaigne spoke several languages - a skill he used to his advantage in securing roles in international productions. He served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and was only one platoon apart in the [[Parris Island]] [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|boot camp]] from his future friend [[Steve McQueen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreatescapelocations.com/Lawrence%20Montaigne.htm|title=New Page 1|work=thegreatescapelocations.com}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in the role of Dr. Chauncy Hartlund in the 1965 ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' episode, \"The Case of the Carefree Coronary.\" In 1966, Montaigne portrayed the [[Romulan]] Decius in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"[[Balance of Terror]]\"; he had nearly been cast as Mr Spock when it was possible that [[Leonard Nimoy]] would appear on ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission Impossible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/as-we-see-it/weekly-qa/2012/aug/08/man-who-would-be-spock/|title=The Man who would be Spock|author=Ken Miller|date=8 August 2012|work=LasVegasWeekly.com}}</ref> A year later, he portrayed the [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]] [[Stonn]], the [[Intimate relationship|paramour]] of [[Spock]]'s intended bride [[T'Pring]], in the episode \"[[Amok Time]]\"\u2014a role that he reprised in 2006 in the unofficial mini-series ''[[Star Trek: Of Gods and Men]]''.\n\nAdditionally, he guest-starred on ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'', ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'', ''[[The Man From U.N.C.L.E.]]'', ''[[Blue Light (TV series)|Blue Light]]'', ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission: Impossible]]'', ''[[The Time Tunnel]]'', ''[[The Invaders]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'', ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]'' and ''[[The Feather and Father Gang]]''.\n\nHis motion picture appearances include roles in ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' (1963),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Captain Sindbad]]'' (1963), ''[[Tobruk (1967 film)|Tobruk]]'' (1967), ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968), ''The Psycho Lover'' (1970), ''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]'' (1975),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Framed (1975 film)|Framed]]'' (1975), ''[[Young Lady Chatterley]]'' (1977),<ref name=NYT /> ''[[Deadly Blessing]]'' (1981)<ref name=NYT /> and ''[[Dakota (1988 film)|Dakota]]'' (1988).<ref name=NYT /> During the 1980s, Montaigne taught film at [[North Texas State University]].\n\nFor some years, Montaigne lived in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], and translated medical texts for a publishing firm. In 2007, Montaigne voiced a guest-starring role in the pilot episode of the web series ''[[Star Trek: The Continuing Mission]]''.\n\nMontaigne died on March 17, 2017, at the age of 86.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/remembering-lawrence-montaigne-1931-2017|title=Remembering Lawrence Montaigne, 1931\u20132017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Selected television appearances ==\n* ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', episode \"The Case of the Carefree Coronary\" as Dr. Chauncy Hartlund (1965)\n* ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'', episode \"[[Balance of Terror]]\" as Decius (1966)\n* ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'', episode \"[[Amok Time]]\" as Stonn (1967)\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Beast from 20,000 Fathoms]]'' || Soldier || Uncredited\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Band Wagon]]'' || Minor Role || Uncredited\n|-\n|1959|| ''Amud Ha'Esh'' || David ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''Rapina al quartiere Ovest'' || ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''Mobby Jackson'' || ||\n|-\n|1961|| ''[[The Mongols (film)|The Mongols]]'' || Prince Stefan's ally ||\n|-\n|1961|| ''[[The Italian Brigands]]'' || O Prevete ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[Damon and Pythias (film)|Damon and Pythias]]'' || Flute Player ||\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[Captain Sindbad]]'' || Jafar ||\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' || Haynes, \"Diversions\" ||\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[Combat!]]'' || Sgt. Koch || Episode: A Rare Vintage\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[The Satan Bug]]'' || Officer at Radar Tracking Station || Uncredited\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Synanon (film)|Synanon]]'' || The Greek ||\n|-\n|1967|| ''[[Tobruk (1967 film)|Tobruk]]'' || Italian Officer ||\n|-\n|1968|| ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' || Briggs ||\n|-\n|1969|| ''[[Topaz (1969 film)|Topaz]]'' || Russian Agent #2 || Uncredited\n|-\n|1970|| ''The Psycho Lover'' || Kenneth Alden ||\n|-\n|1971|| ''[[Bearcats!]]'' || Koster || 1 episode\n|-\n|1975|| ''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]'' || Ubermann ||\n|-\n|1975|| ''[[Framed (1975 film)|Framed]]'' || Deputy Allison ||\n|-\n|1977|| ''[[Young Lady Chatterley]]'' || Carl \u2013 Chauffeur ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Everything Happens to Me (1980 film)|Everything Happens to Me]]'' || Military Sergeant ||\n|-\n|1981|| ''[[Deadly Blessing]]'' || Matthew Gluntz ||\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[Dakota (1988 film)|Dakota]]'' || Mr. Diamond ||\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0598807}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=134149|name=Lawrence Montaigne}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lawrencemontaigne.com/|Montaigne's Web}}  Lawrence Montaigne's Personal Website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Montaigne, Lawrence}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:American translators]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American stunt performers]]\n", "name_user": "Dana90604", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected television appearances", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawrence_Montaigne"}
